{"title_page": "Leo Determan", "text_new": "{{short description|Sailor from Finland}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox sailor\n  | name           = Leo Determan\n  | image          = Leo Determan.png\n  | image_size     = \n  | caption        = Leo Determan in 2017 as spectator during the Soling Worlds at Muiden, The Netherlands\n  | birth_name     =\n  | fullname       = \n  | nickname       = Deet\n  | nationality    = {{NED}}\n  | birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1949|4|7}}\n  | birth_place    = [[Rotterdam]]\n  | death_date     =\n  | death_place    =\n  | height         = {{convert|1.92|m|ft|abbr=on}}\n  | weight         =\n  | retired        =\n  | classes        = [[Flying Dutchman (dinghy)|Flying Dutchman]]<br />[[Tempest (keelboat)|Tempest]]<br />[[Soling]]\n  | club           = [[:nl:Vriendschap Zij Ons Doel|VZOD]], Rotterdam\n  | collegeteam    =\n  | coach          =\n  | medaltemplates-title =\n  | medaltemplates = \n    {{Medal|Country|{{NED}}}}\n      {{MedalCompetition|[[Vintage Yachting Games]]}}\n        {{Medal|Gold|2008 [[Medemblik]], [[Netherlands|The Netherlands]]|[[2008 Vintage Yachting Games \u2013 Soling|Soling]]}}\n  | show-medals    = yes\n  | updated        = 8 April 2020\n}}\n\n'''Leo Determan''' (born 7 April 1949 in [[Rotterdam]]) is a [[sailor]] from the [[Netherlands]], who represented his country at the [[2008 Vintage Yachting Games]] in [[Medemblik]] [[Netherlands|The Netherlands]]. Determan in the middle together with [[helmsman]] [[Rudy den Outer]] and [[Ronald den Arend]] on the foredeck took the [[Gold medal]] in the [[Soling]]. <ref name=\"Vintage\" /> \nLeo holds several Dutch titles (1995, 1999, 2000, 2008 and 2001) and one Italian (2010) title in the [[Soling National Champions|Soling]]. He used to be member of Yacht Club ''VZOD'', Rotterdam.\n[[File:VYG 1 Soling 2008.JPG|thumb|left|Leo Determan (middle) with Rudy den Outer and Ronald den Arend winning the [[2008 Vintage Yachting Games]] in [[Medemblik]].]]\n{{clear}}\n\n==Sailing==\nAfter sailing as crew on a \"Vrijheid\", Determan purchased the Flying Dutchman H 125 \"Aquarius\" in 1970. With [[Rudy den Outer]] he sailed Flying Dutchman, Spanker (a Dutch National class) and [[Soling]] for many years and for a brief period [[Tempest (keelboat)|Tempest]] depending on the class they changed positions as crew or helmsman.\n[[File:FD H125.jpg|left|thumb|Leo Determan (right) and Rudy den Outer in the Flying Dutchman ''Aquarius'' on the Kralingsche Plas, Netherlands in 1970]]\n{{clear}}\n\n== Personal/Professional life ==\nDeterman is married with Yvonne and lives in [[Vierpolders]], The Netherlands and works in the [[petrochemical|(petro)chemical]] industry. In 2005 [[:nl:Gulf Oil|Gulf Oil Nederland]] BV in [[Den Helder]] named her new [[Tanker (ship)|Tank ship]] after Determan. <ref name=\"Tanker\" /><ref name=\"Tanker2\" />\n[[File:De Leo Determan (Tanker).jpg|left|thumb|Dutch Tankership \"Leo Determan\"]]\n{{clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs =\n <ref name=Tanker>{{cite web\n   |url        = https://www.debinnenvaart.nl/schip_detail/7154/\n   |title      = LEO DETERMAN\n   |publisher  = Vereniging \"De Binnenvaart\"\n   |accessdate = 8 April 2020\n  }}</ref>\n <ref name=Tanker2>{{cite web\n   |url        = https://www.marinetraffic.com/nl/ais/details/ships/shipid:242854/mmsi:244700188/imo:0/vessel:LEO_DETERMAN\n   |title      = LEO DETERMAN\n   |publisher  = Marine Traffic\n   |accessdate = 8 April 2020\n  }}</ref>\n <ref name=Vintage>{{cite web\n   |url=http://www.soling.com/results/ShowResults.asp?ID=459\n   |title=Vintage Yachting Games 2008\n   |year=2008\n   |website=www.soling.com\n   |publisher=International Soling Association|location=Buenos Aires (ARG)\n   |access-date=8 April 2015\n }}</ref>\n}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Determan, Leo}}\n[[Category:1949 births]]\n[[Category:Dutch male sailors (sport)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Flying Dutchman class sailors]]\n[[Category:Soling class sailors]]\n{{Footer Dutch Champions in Soling}}\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Rotterdam]]\n\n{{Netherlands-yachtracing-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Sailor from Finland}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox sailor\n  | name           = Leo Determan\n  | image          = Leo Determan.png\n  | image_size     = \n  | caption        = Leo Determan in 2017 as spectator during the Soling Worlds at Muiden, The Netherlands\n  | birth_name     =\n  | fullname       = \n  | nickname       = Deet\n  | nationality    = {{NED}}\n  | birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1949|4|7}}\n  | birth_place    = [[Rotterdam]]\n  | death_date     =\n  | death_place    =\n  | height         = {{convert|1.92|m|ft|abbr=on}}\n  | weight         =\n  | retired        =\n  | classes        = [[Flying Dutchman (dinghy)|Flying Dutchman]]<br />[[Tempest (keelboat)|Tempest]]<br />[[Soling]]\n  | club           = [[:nl:Vriendschap Zij Ons Doel|VZOD]], Rotterdam\n  | collegeteam    =\n  | coach          =\n  | medaltemplates-title =\n  | medaltemplates = \n    {{Medal|Country|{{NED}}}}\n      {{MedalCompetition|[[Vintage Yachting Games]]}}\n        {{Medal|Gold|2008 [[Medemblik]], [[Netherlands|The Netherlands]]|[[2008 Vintage Yachting Games \u2013 Soling|Soling]]}}\n  | show-medals    = yes\n  | updated        = 8 April 2020\n}}\n\n'''Leo Determan''' (born 7 April 1949 in [[Rotterdam]]) is a [[sailor]] from the [[Netherlands]], who represented his country at the [[2008 Vintage Yachting Games]] in [[Medemblik]] [[Netherlands|The Netherlands]]. Determan in the middle together with [[helmsman]] [[Rudy den Outer]] and [[Ronald den Arend]] on the foredeck took the [[Gold medal]] in the [[Soling]]. <ref name=\"Vintage\" /> \nLeo holds several Dutch titles (1995, 1999, 2000, 2008 and 2001) and one Italian (2010) title in the [[Soling National Champions|Soling]]. He used to be member of Yacht Club ''VZOD'', Rotterdam.\n[[File:VYG 1 Soling 2008.JPG|thumb|left|Leo Determan (middle) with Rudy den Outer and Ronald den Arend winning the [[2008 Vintage Yachting Games]] in [[Medemblik]].]]\n{{clear}}\n\n==Sailing==\nAfter sailing as crew on a \"Vrijheid\" Determan purchased the Flying Dutchman H 125 \"Aquarius\" in 1970. With [[Rudy den Outer]] he sailed Flying Dutchman, Spanker (a Dutch National class) and [[Soling]] for many years and for a brief period [[Tempest (keelboat)|Tempest]] depending on the class they changed positions as crew or helmsman.\n[[File:FD H125.jpg|left|thumb|Leo Determan (right) and Rudy den Outer in the Flying Dutchman ''Aquarius'' on the Kralingsche Plas, Netherlands in 1970]]\n{{clear}}\n== Personal/Professional life ==\nDeterman is married with Yvonne and lives in [[Vierpolders]], The Netherlands and works in the [[petrochemical|(petro)chemical]] industry. In 2005 [[:nl:Gulf Oil|Gulf Oil Nederland]] BV in [[Den Helder]] named her new [[Tanker (ship)|Tank ship]] after Determan. <ref name=\"Tanker\" /><ref name=\"Tanker2\" />\n[[File:De Leo Determan (Tanker).jpg|left|thumb|Dutch Tankership \"Leo Determan\"]]\n{{clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs =\n <ref name=Tanker>{{cite web\n   |url        = https://www.debinnenvaart.nl/schip_detail/7154/\n   |title      = LEO DETERMAN\n   |publisher  = Vereniging \"De Binnenvaart\"\n   |accessdate = 8 April 2020\n  }}</ref>\n <ref name=Tanker2>{{cite web\n   |url        = https://www.marinetraffic.com/nl/ais/details/ships/shipid:242854/mmsi:244700188/imo:0/vessel:LEO_DETERMAN\n   |title      = LEO DETERMAN\n   |publisher  = Marine Traffic\n   |accessdate = 8 April 2020\n  }}</ref>\n <ref name=Vintage>{{cite web\n   |url=http://www.soling.com/results/ShowResults.asp?ID=459\n   |title=Vintage Yachting Games 2008\n   |year=2008\n   |website=www.soling.com\n   |publisher=International Soling Association|location=Buenos Aires (ARG)\n   |access-date=8 April 2015\n }}</ref>\n}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Determan, Leo}}\n[[Category:1949 births]]\n[[Category:Dutch male sailors (sport)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Flying Dutchman class sailors]]\n[[Category:Soling class sailors]]\n{{Footer Dutch Champions in Soling}}\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Rotterdam]]\n\n{{Netherlands-yachtracing-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Dragon Genoa", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSailing", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Leo_Determan"}
{"title_page": "Bridget Hodson", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{Notability|Biographies|date=April 2020}}\n{{BLP sources|date=April 2020}}\n}}\n{{Infobox person\n| image       = \n| imagesize   = \n| caption     = \n| birth_name   = \n| birth_date   = \n| birth_place  = [[United Kingdom]]\n| death_date   = \n| occupation  = Film/television actress\n| years_active = 1983, 1994&ndash;present\n| spouse      = \n| homepage    =\n}}\n\n'''Bridget \"Biddy\" Hodson''' is an English [[actress]] better known for her roles of [[Elaine (legend)|Elaine]] in the mini-series ''[[The Mists of Avalon (TV miniseries)|The Mists of Avalon]]'' and [[Ilsa Haupstein]] in the film ''[[Hellboy (2004 film)|Hellboy]]''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2004/film/markets-festivals/hellboy-1200534276/|title=Hellboy|last=Leydon|first=Joe|last2=Leydon|first2=Joe|date=2004-03-29|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-2004-apr-02-et-dargis2-story.html|title=A day-glo hero who's flatter off the page|date=2004-04-02|website=Los Angeles Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>. She used the stage name Biddy Hodson from 1983 to 2004 and her name Bridget Hodson from 2004 onwards.\n\n==Filmography==\n{| border=\"2\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"margin: 1em 1em 1em 0; background: #f9f9f9; border: 1px #aaa solid; border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 90%;\"\n|- bgcolor=\"#CCCCCC\" align=\"center\"\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n|1983|| ''[[St. Ursula's in Danger]]'' || Kitty || [[Television film|TV movie]]\n|-\n|1994|| ''[[Loaded (1994 film)|Loaded]]'' || Charlotte ||\n|-\n|1995|| ''[[A Mind to Murder (film)|A Mind to Murder]]'' || Jennifer Priddy || TV movie\n|-\n|1995|| ''[[Cracker (UK TV series)|Cracker]]'' || Carol Barker || Episode: \"True Romance: Part 1\"\n|-\n|1996|| ''[[Soldier Soldier]]'' || [[Second Lieutenant|2nd Lt]] Samantha Sheridan || 8 episodes\n|-\n|1996|| ''[[Heartbea