rams || 2 episodes\n|-\n|2001|| ''[[The Mists of Avalon (TV miniseries)|The Mists of Avalon]]'' || [[Elaine (legend)|Elaine]] || 2 episodes\n|-\n|2001|| ''[[Beginner's Luck (2001 film)|Beginner's Luck]]'' || Minnie ||\n|-\n|2002-2005|| ''[[Doctors (2000 TV series)|Doctors]]'' || Mary Lawson / Julie Marsden || 2 episodes\n|-\n|2004|| ''[[Hellboy (2004 film)|Hellboy]]'' || [[Ilsa Haupstein]] || (as Bridget Hodson)\n|-\n|2008|| ''[[Doctor Who]]'' || [[List of UNIT personnel#Captain Marian Price|Captain Marian Price]] || 2 episodes, (final appearance)\n|}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|id=0388336|name=Biddy Hodson}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hodson, Bridget}}\n[[Category:English film actresses]]\n[[Category:English television actresses]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "name_user": "Cardiffbear88", "label": "safe", "comment": "Reflist", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bridget_Hodson"}
{"title_page": "Baptismal font at St Bartholomew's Church, Li\u00e8ge", "text_new": "[[File:Renier de Huy JPG0.jpg|thumb|right|300px|''[[Baptism of Jesus|Baptism of Christ]]'' on the [[Li\u00e8ge]] font]]\n[[File:Renier de Huy MCL1.jpg|thumb|300px|Another view of the font]]\nThe '''baptismal font at St Bartholomew's Church, Li\u00e8ge''' is a [[Romanesque art|Romanesque]] [[brass]] or [[bronze]] [[baptismal font]] made between 1107 and 1118 now in [[Collegiate Church of St. Bartholomew|St Bartholomew's Church, Li\u00e8ge]] in [[Li\u00e8ge (city)|Li\u00e8ge]], [[Belgium]].  The font is a major masterpiece of [[Mosan art]], remarkable for the classicism of its style, whose origin has been the subject of great debate among [[art historian]]s. The [[Meuse River]] valley in modern Belgium and France, roughly coterminous with the [[Diocese of Li\u00e8ge]], was the leading 12th-century centre of Romanesque metalwork, which was still the most prestigious medium in art.\n\n==History==\nThe Li\u00e8ge font was commissioned after 1107 and completed by 1118 for the church of Notre-Dame-aux-Fonts (\"[[Blessed Virgin Mary|Our Lady]]'s with the font\"), which abutted [[St. Lambert's Cathedral, Li\u00e8ge|the old Li\u00e8ge Cathedral]] and functioned as the [[baptistry]] for the city.<ref>Beckwith, 178. See Xhayet and Halleux, 123, note 17 for a fuller account of the status of the church and its priest.</ref> These dates are based on the period of office of the Abb\u00e9 Hellin, parish priest of the church, known to have commissioned it, for in his obituary in the contemporary ''{{lang|la|Chronicon Rythmicum Leodiense}}'' ({{lang-en|Li\u00e8ge Rhyming Chronicle}}) the font is clearly described, though with no mention of the artist.<ref>Xhayet and Halleux, 21 (quotes chronicle) and 122\u2013123</ref>  Both cathedral and church were destroyed during the French Revolution, and the font was hidden for safe-keeping before being moved to its present location in 1804. The Li\u00e8ge chronicle describes a cover with figures of the [[Four Evangelists]] and prophets, presumably also in metal, which was lost during the Revolution, along with  two of the supporting oxen.<ref>Xhayet and Halleux, 21 and 123 and Li\u00e8ge City Tourism</ref>  The present stone plinth and setting replaced in the 20th century a solid round stone one built in 1804.<ref>{{citation|first=Henry|last=Rousseaux|title=Bulletin des Mus\u00e9es Royaux d'arts d\u00e9coratifs et industriels|chapter=Les fonts baptismaux de Saint Barth\u00e9l\u00e9my \u00e0 Li\u00e8ge|language=French| url=https://archive.org/stream/bulletin06musuoft#page/58/mode/2up/search/barthel|year=1907|pages=58\u201360}}</ref><ref>See [[:File:Baptismal font of St Barthelemy Church - Liege - 1846 .jpg|old photos on Commons]]</ref>  The font is still used for baptisms today; there is normally a small charge for viewing it.<ref>Li\u00e8ge City Tourism</ref>\n\n==Renier de Huy==\n[[File:Renier de Huy MCL3.jpg|thumb|300px|left|Detail of [[John the Baptist]] baptising the two neophytes.]]\nThe font was traditionally attributed to [[Renier de Huy]], a 12th-century metalworker and sculptor, but this, and even the Mosan origin of the font, have been questioned and alternative theories advanced.  Nothing is known of Rainer's life other than that he was mentioned in a document of 1125 as a [[goldsmith]],<ref>Beckwith, 178</ref> but a 14th-century [[chronicle]] mentions him as the artist of the font.<ref>Oxford</ref>  He may have died about 1150.<ref>Beckwith, 178. The Getty Union Artist Names List has him active until 1144 [http://www.getty.edu/vow/ULANFullDisplay?find=Rainer+of+Huy&role=&nation=&prev_page=1&subjectid=500081355]</ref>  Another equally shadowy figure in Mosan metalwork from the next generation, [[Godefroid de Huy]] or de Claire, also came from the small but prosperous city of [[Huy]] on the Meuse.\n\nThe only other work generally agreed to be by the same master as the font is a small bronze [[crucifix]] ([[Schn\u00fctgen Museum]], [[Cologne]]);<ref>Lasko, 181</ref> another in [[Brussels]] has many similarities.<ref>Illustrated in Xhayet and Halleux, before p. 129</ref> A censer in similar style is attributed to Renier or a follower by many.<ref>Lasko</ref>\n\n==Style and origin==\nThe figures on the font are in very high [[relief]], and have a remarkable classicism of style; so much so that it has also been suggested that it was in fact made in [[Constantinople]],<ref>Oxford</ref> or by Greeks in [[Rome]] about 1000.  Other explanations attribute the classicism to close [[Byzantine art|Byzantine]] influence,<ref>Henderson (1967), 46, Gombrich and others</ref> though as Honour and Fleming point out, \"In bodily proportions, poses, gestures and garments, they recall Classical models far beyond Byzantine, Carolingian, or even Early Christian art\"; they suggest the artist might have seen ancient Greek sculptures in Constantinople when on the [[First Crusade]].<ref>Honour & Fleming, 288 [https://books.google.com/books?id=qGb4pyoseH4C&pg=PT385&dq=Rainer+of+Huy&as_brr=3&cd=7#v=onepage&q=Rainer%20of%20Huy&f=false online text]. See also Beckwith, 178\u2013179</ref>  Other writers explain the style as emerging from older Mosan and [[Carolingian art|Carolingian]] traditions, with recent Byzantine influence, and prefiguring [[Gothic art|Gothic]] figure style.<ref>Beckwith, 178\u2013179, Henderson (1967), 46\u201348</ref>  The idealized figures are modelled in rounded forms;  several nude figures are present, and one is seen from behind in a three-quarters view, a sophisticated classical pose.\n\nArt-historical argument over the origin of the font has been vigorous and sometimes acrimonious, and in recent decades mostly conducted in French.<ref>Xhayet and Halleux, 117, 199</ref>  In support of the Byzantine origin theory, analysis of the [[lead (metal)|lead]] in 1993 has shown that it came from mines in [[Spain]] or [[Sardinia]], whereas other Mosan works used locally sourced metal.<ref>Xhayet and Halleux, 101\u2013103; see also note 19 on p. 124, and Li\u00e8ge City Tourism</ref>  Pierre Colman and his wife Berthe Lhoist-Colman have developed a \"Roman\" theory, according to which the [[Holy Roman Emperor Otto III]] commissioned the font from Greek craftsmen in Rome in about 1000, as a gift for the [[Basilica of Saint John Lateran]] there.<ref>Colman and Lhoist-Colman, 2003.</ref> Decades later it was carried off by [[Henry IV, Holy Roman Emperor|Henry IV]] or [[Henry V, Holy Roman Emperor|Henry V]] to the Meuse.<ref>Xhayet and Halleux, 99\u2013101, who do not accept this theory.</ref> However most art historians continue to accept the traditional Mosan attribution, and relate the style to the other works mentioned above.\n\n==Description==\n[[File:00 Fonts batismaux - Renier de Huy.JPG|thumb|270px|Saint [[John the Baptist]] preaching, the start of the sequence of scenes]]\n[[File:Renier de Huy JPG01.jpg|thumb|270px|The last two scenes]]\n\nThe basin is {{convert|91|cm|in}} across at the top, tapering slightly towards the base, and is  variously described as of [[brass]] or [[bronze]].<ref>The two terms for copper alloys have some overlap.</ref> It was made by [[lost wax]] casting, with the basin cast in a single piece; the size was not necessarily exceptional, as both church bells and cauldrons for large households were probably cast at comparable sizes; some church doors cast in a single piece, though flat, were much larger.  The font sat on twelve oxen (two are now missing), who emerged from a stone [[plinth]], a reference to the \"molten sea... on twelve oxen\" cast in bronze for [[Solomon's temple]]<ref>{{bibleverse|1|Kings|7:23-7:27|NIV}}; this feature is today typical of fonts in [[The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints]].</ref>  The five scenes shown, identified by Latin inscriptions (\"tituli\") on the rim above and in the image field, can be read in chronological sequence:<ref>See the continuous diagram at Xhayet and Halleux, 124; the scenes are covered in great detail in the pages following; also Calkins, 128</ref><ref>{{cite web\n |url         = http://www.st-barthelemy.be/Gifs/graphique_lineaire.gif\n |title       = Linear graphic of Baptismal font at St Bartholomew's  Church (official website)\n |publisher   = ASBL \"Art et Histoire - Saint-Barth\u00e9lemy - Li\u00e8ge\"\n |work        = Picture\n |archiveurl  = https://www.webcitation.org/5mva3yNy3?url=http://www.st-barthelemy.be/Gifs/graphique_lineaire.gif\n |archivedate = 2010-01-20\n |url-status     = dead\n |access-date = 2010-01-20\n}} (in French)</ref>\n\n*[[John the Baptist]] preaching to four figures, the last on the right in full military gear; followed by a [[ficus|fig]] tree.<ref>Xhayet and Halleux, 124-6</ref>\n*John baptising two neophytes, with two further figures to the right, who probably represent the two disciples John told to follow Jesus (John 1:35\u201337).  As often in Early Medieval art, the attempt to convey the [[River Jordan]] stretching away in [[graphical perspective|perspective]] has it rise up like a mound.  A [[Arecaceae|palm]] tree follows.<ref>Xhayet and Halleux, 126-9</ref>\n*The ''[[Baptism of Jesus|Baptism of Christ]]'' by John the Baptist, a commonly represented scene, again with the water piling up like a mound.  Jesus is beardless and young, as is also typical. The angel to the right of Jesus has his hands veiled with a cloth, a mark of respect in Eastern [[liturgy]], though it may also simply represent a cloth ready for Jesus to dry himself with.  An [[olive]] tree follows.<ref>Xhayet and Halleux, 129\u2013131</ref>\n*[[Saint Peter]] baptising  [[Cornelius the Centurion]], the first [[gentile]] to be baptised  ([[Acts]] 10), with a sponsor or godfather.  The [[Hand of God (art)|Hand of God]] appears from above to signal approval.<ref>Xhayet and Halleux, 131-32</ref>\n*Saint [[John the Evangelist]] baptising the \"philosopher [[Craton]]\", also with a sponsor and Hand. A [[vine]] follows.  The story of Craton comes from [[apocryphal]] writings such as the account of John's life by the [[Pseudo-Abdias]].<ref>Cartlidge and Elliott, 195; for a full account in French see Xhayet and Halleux, 199ff, and 132-33.</ref>\n[[File:Fonts baptismaux.jpg|thumb|left|100px|Baptismal font of [[Furnaux]] also inspired by Rupert de Deutz]]\nExcept for the last two the scenes are separated by trees which are stylised in typical Romanesque fashion, but whose leaf shapes are all different.<ref>See the comparison at Xhayet and Halleux, 127, where each is identified as respectively fig, vine, olive and palm.</ref>  A continuous undulating ground-line runs all round the basin.  Other inscriptions run round the top and bottom rims of the basin.<ref>Xhayet and Halleux, 94\u201398 give the texts.  These are a number of [[hexameter]]s of [[Leonine verse]], the upper ones explaining the relief scenes while the lower one explains the oxen: \"By the twelve oxen is shown the ''[[Typology (theology)|forma]]'' [type] of pastors, through the example of whose apostolic life, full of grace, and their elevated office, the citizens are purified, and the spirit of these waters refreshes the holy city\" (approximate translation)</ref>  While the baptism of Jesus is very commonly depicted in Early Medieval art, those of the other figures are very rare subjects indeed,<ref>St Peter baptising an unspecified figure is shown on an ivory book cover of c. 900 in Florence, in a similar composition which also has a layperson to the right of the font, holding textiles (the naked catchumen's clothes, or a towel) which veil his hands in a similar way to the angel in the Baptism of Jesus scene here. Lasko, plate 63</ref> and this unusually elaborate and learned programme was no doubt composed with clerical assistance. It does not reflect Byzantine [[iconographic]] precedents; instead it matches closely the interest in [[typology (theology)|typology]] and [[allegory]], of which the influential contemporary Li\u00e8ge-born theologian [[Rupert of Deutz]] was a particular exponent (though Rupert was also a particular opponent of the bishop at the time, [[Otbert of Li\u00e8ge]], who took the Emperor's side in the [[Investiture Controversy]]).<ref>Xhayet and Halleux, 133, and 122 on their dispute. See also Henderson (1977), 229</ref>  The head of [[God the Father]] that appears at the top of the ''Baptism of Christ'' (identified as <small>PATER</small>) is an early appearance of [[God the Father in Western art]]; a [[Hand of God (art)|Hand of God]], more typical of the period, appears in the baptism scenes of Cornelius and Craton.\n\nThe baptismal font in the little village of [[Furnaux]] ([[Mettet]]), relatively far from [[Li\u00e8ge]] but at that time in the same [[diocese]], has the same theological background linking [[Rupert de Deutz]]'s theological vision where the [[Old Testament]] and [[New Testament]] are closely linked.\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|2}}\n{{Commons category|Baptismal font of Renier de Huy, Li\u00e8ge}}\n\n== References ==\n*Beckwith, John.  ''Early Medieval Art: Carolingian, Ottonian, Romanesque'', Thames & Hudson, 1964 (rev. 1969), {{ISBN|0-500-20019-X}}\n*Calkins, Robert G.; ''Monuments of Medieval Art'', Dutton, 1979, {{ISBN|0-525-47561-3}}\n*Cartlidge, David R. and Elliott, James Keith, ''Art and the Christian Apocrypha'', Routledge, 2001, {{ISBN|0-415-23392-5}}, {{ISBN|978-0-415-23392-7}}, [https://books.google.com/books?id=o0LBvOMYArYC&pg=PA195&dq=John+baptising+the+philosopher+Craton&cd=1#v=onepage&q=&f=false Google books]\n*{{citation|last1=Colman |first1=Pierre  |last2=Lhoist-Colman|first2=Berthe   |title=Les   fonts baptismaux de Saint-Barth\u00e9lemy \u00e0 Li\u00e8ge - Chef-d'oeuvre sans pareil et noeud de   controverses|publisher=Acad\u00e9mie Royale de Belgique|year=2003|isbn=2-8031-0189-0|language=French}}\n*Henderson, George. ''Gothic Art'', 1967, Penguin, {{ISBN|0-14-020806-2}}\n*Henderson, George. ''Early Medieval Art'', 1972, rev. 1977, Penguin.\n*[[Hugh Honour]] and John Fleming, ''A World History of Art'', 1st edn. 1982 & later editions, Macmillan, London, page refs to 1984 Macmillan 1st edn. paperback. {{ISBN|0-333-37185-2}}\n*Kleiner, Fred S., Christin J. Mamiya, and Helen Gardner. ''Gardner's Art Through the Ages''. Belmont: Wadsworth, 2004\n*[[Peter Lasko|Lasko, Peter]], ''Ars Sacra'', Penguin History of Art (now Yale)\n*{{Cite journal|last=Martinot|first=L.|last2=Tricherini|first2=P.|last3=Guillaume|first3=J.|date=|year=1997|title=Le r\u00f4le des m\u00e9thodes de laboratoire dans la recherche de la provenance de dinanderies m\u00e9di\u00e9vales. Application aux fonts baptismaux de Tirlemont, aux chandeliers des abbayes de Postel et de Parc des Mus\u00e9es Royaux d'Art et d'Histoire de Bruxelles et aux fonts baptismaux de Saint-Barth\u00e9lemy \u00e0 Li\u00e8ge|url=|journal=Acad\u00e9mie Royale de Belgique. Bulletin de la Classe des Beaux-Arts|language=fr|volume=8|pages=19\u201336|via=}}\n*[https://archive.is/20020221131529/http://www.liege.be/visitelg/tourisme/patrirel/anglais/baptfont.htm#e City of Li\u00e8ge Tourism, with good feature], and a bibliography of recent scholarship in French. Accessed 10 Jan. 2010\n*\"Oxford\": Rainer of Huy: ''The Oxford Dictionary of Art.'' Accessed 10 Jan. 2010, [http://www.enotes.com/oxford-art-encyclopedia/rainer-huy]\n*Swarzenski, Hanns. ''Monuments of Romanesque Art; The Art of Church Treasures in North-Western Europe'', [[Faber and Faber]], 1974, {{ISBN|0-571-10588-2}}\n*Xhayet, Genevi\u00e8ve and Halleux, Robert (eds), ''\u00c9tudes sur les fonts baptismaux de Saint-Barth\u00e9l\u00e9my \u00e0 Li\u00e8ge'', Editions du CEFAL, 2006, {{ISBN|2-87130-212-X}}, 9782871302124 [https://books.google.com/books?id=FBM-v_6uzpwC&pg=PA99&dq=Pierre+Colman,+Les+fonts+baptismaux+de+Saint-Barth%C3%A9lemy&cd=2#v=onepage&q=Pierre%20Colman%2C%20Les%20fonts%20baptismaux%20de%20Saint-Barth%C3%A9lemy&f=false google books]\n\n==External links==\n* {{cite web| url=http://www.kikirpa.be/www2/cgi-bin/wwwopac.exe?DATABASE=fotos2&LANGUAGE=0&COPYTEXT=&COPYRIGHT=&OPAC_URL=&10060034=on| title=Detailed picture gallery of Baptismal font at St Bartholomew's Church of Li\u00e8ge|accessdate=2010-01-20|publisher=Royal Institute for the Study and Conservation of Belgium's Artistic Heritage|work=Picture Library}} (in French)\n* {{cite web| url= http://www.st-barthelemy.be/Galerie_FB/Gal_Tof.htm| title= Picture gallery of Baptismal font at St Bartholomew's  Church (official website)| accessdate= 2010-01-20| publisher= ASBL \"Art et Histoire - Saint-Barth\u00e9lemy - Li\u00e8ge\"| work= Picture  Library| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100113133432/http://www.st-barthelemy.be/Galerie_FB/Gal_Tof.htm| archivedate= 2010-01-13| url-status= dead}} (in French)\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Baptismal Font At St Bartholomew's Church, Liege}}\n[[Category:Baptismal fonts]]\n[[Category:Bronze sculptures in Belgium]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic churches in Li\u00e8ge|*]]\n[[Category:History of Li\u00e8ge]]\n[[Category:Medieval European sculptures]]\n[[Category:Mosan art]]\n[[Category:Walloon culture]]\n[[Category:Medieval European metalwork objects]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Renier de Huy JPG0.jpg|thumb|right|300px|''[[Baptism of Jesus|Baptism of Christ]]'' on the [[Li\u00e8ge]] font]]\n[[File:Renier de Huy MCL1.jpg|thumb|300px|Another view of the font]]\nThe '''baptismal font at St Bartholomew's Church, Li\u00e8ge''' is a [[Romanesque art|Romanesque]] [[brass]] or [[bronze]] [[baptismal font]] made between 1107 and 1118 now in [[Collegiate Church of St. Bartholomew|St Bartholomew's Church, Li\u00e8ge]] in [[Li\u00e8ge (city)|Li\u00e8ge]], [[Belgium]].  The font is a major masterpiece of [[Mosan art]], remarkable for the classicism of its style, whose origin has been the subject of great debate among [[art historian]]s. The [[Meuse River]] valley in modern Belgium and France, roughly coterminous with the [[Diocese of Li\u00e8ge]], was the leading 12th-century centre of Romanesque metalwork, which was still the most prestigious medium in art.\n\n==History==\nThe Li\u00e8ge font was commissioned after 1107 and completed by 1118 for the church of Notre-Dame-aux-Fonts (\"[[Blessed Virgin Mary|Our Lady]]'s with the font\"), which abutted [[St. Lambert's Cathedral, Li\u00e8ge|the old Li\u00e8ge Cathedral]] and functioned as the [[baptistry]] for the city.<ref>Beckwith, 178. See Xhayet and Halleux, 123, note 17 for a fuller account of the status of the church and its priest.</ref> These dates are based on the period of office of the Abb\u00e9 Hellin, parish priest of the church, known to have commissioned it, for in his obituary in the contemporary ''{{lang|la|Chronicon Rythmicum Leodiense}}'' ({{lang-en|Li\u00e8ge Rhyming Chronicle}}) the font is clearly described, though with no mention of the artist.<ref>Xhayet and Halleux, 21 (quotes chronicle) and 122\u2013123</ref>  Both cathedral and church were destroyed during the French Revolution, and the font was hidden for safe-keeping before being moved to its present location in 1804. The Li\u00e8ge chronicle describes a cover with figures of the [[Four Evangelists]] and prophets, presumably also in metal, which was lost during the Revolution, along with  two of the supporting oxen.<ref>Xhayet and Halleux, 21 and 123 and Li\u00e8ge City Tourism</ref>  The present stone plinth and setting replaced in the 20th century a solid round stone one built in 1804.<ref>{{citation|first=Henry|last=Rousseaux|title=Bulletin des Mus\u00e9es Royaux d'arts d\u00e9coratifs et industriels|chapter=Les fonts baptismaux de Saint Barth\u00e9l\u00e9my \u00e0 Li\u00e8ge|language=French| url=https://archive.org/stream/bulletin06musuoft#page/58/mode/2up/search/barthel|year=1907|pages=58\u201360}}</ref><ref>See [[:File:Baptismal font of St Barthelemy Church - Liege - 1846 .jpg|old photos on Commons]]</ref>  The font is still used for baptisms today; there is normally a small charge for viewing it.<ref>Li\u00e8ge City Tourism</ref>\n\n==Renier de Huy==\n[[File:Renier de Huy MCL3.jpg|thumb|300px|left|Detail of [[John the Baptist]] baptising the two neophytes.]]\nThe font was traditionally attributed to [[Renier de Huy]], a 12th-century metalworker and sculptor, but this, and even the Mosan origin of the font, have been questioned and alternative theories advanced.  Nothing is known of Rainer's life other than that he was mentioned in a document of 1125 as a [[goldsmith]],<ref>Beckwith, 178</ref> but a 14th-century [[chronicle]] mentions him as the artist of the font.<ref>Oxford</ref>  He may have died about 1150.<ref>Beckwith, 178. The Getty Union Artist Names List has him active until 1144 [http://www.getty.edu/vow/ULANFullDisplay?find=Rainer+of+Huy&role=&nation=&prev_page=1&subjectid=500081355]</ref>  Another equally shadowy figure in Mosan metalwork from the next generation, [[Godefroid de Huy]] or de Claire, also came from the small but prosperous city of [[Huy]] on the Meuse.\n\nThe only other work generally agreed to be by the same master as the font is a small bronze [[crucifix]] ([[Schn\u00fctgen Museum]], [[Cologne]]);<ref>Lasko, 181</ref> another in [[Brussels]] has many similarities.<ref>Illustrated in Xhayet and Halleux, before p. 129</ref> A censer in similar style is attributed to Renier or a follower by many.<ref>Lasko</ref>\n\n==Style and origin==\nThe figures on the font are in very high [[relief]], and have a remarkable classicism of style; so much so that it has also been suggested that it was in fact made in [[Constantinople]],<ref>Oxford</ref> or by Greeks in [[Rome]] about 1000.  Other explanations attribute the classicism to close [[Byzantine art|Byzantine]] influence,<ref>Henderson (1967), 46, Gombrich and others</ref> though as Honour and Fleming point out, \"In bodily proportions, poses, gestures and garments, they recall Classical models far beyond Byzantine, Carolingian, or even Early Christian art\"; they suggest the artist might have seen ancient Greek sculptures in Constantinople when on the [[First Crusade]].<ref>Honour & Fleming, 288 [https://books.google.com/books?id=qGb4pyoseH4C&pg=PT385&dq=Rainer+of+Huy&as_brr=3&cd=7#v=onepage&q=Rainer%20of%20Huy&f=false online text]. See also Beckwith, 178\u2013179</ref>  Other writers explain the style as emerging from older Mosan and [[Carolingian art|Carolingian]] traditions, with recent Byzantine influence, and prefiguring [[Gothic art|Gothic]] figure style.<ref>Beckwith, 178\u2013179, Henderson (1967), 46\u201348</ref>  The idealized figures are modelled in rounded forms;  several nude figures are present, and one is seen from behind in a three-quarters view, a sophisticated classical pose.\n\nArt-historical argument over the origin of the font has been vigorous and sometimes acrimonious, and in recent decades mostly conducted in French.<ref>Xhayet and Halleux, 117, 199</ref>  In support of the Byzantine origin theory, analysis of the [[lead (metal)|lead]] in 1993 has shown that it came from mines in [[Spain]] or [[Sardinia]], whereas other Mosan works used locally sourced metal.<ref>Xhayet and Halleux, 101\u2013103; see also note 19 on p. 124, and Li\u00e8ge City Tourism</ref>  Pierre Colman and his wife Berthe Lhoist-Colman have developed a \"Roman\" theory, according to which the [[Holy Roman Emperor Otto III]] commissioned the font from Greek craftsmen in Rome in about 1000, as a gift for the [[Basilica of Saint John Lateran]] there.<ref>Colman and Lhoist-Colman, 2003.</ref> Decades later it was carried off by [[Henry IV, Holy Roman Emperor|Henry IV]] or [[Henry V, Holy Roman Emperor|Henry V]] to the Meuse.<ref>Xhayet and Halleux, 99\u2013101, who do not accept this theory.</ref> However most art historians continue to accept the traditional Mosan attribution, and relate the style to the other works mentioned above.\n\n==Description==\n[[File:00 Fonts batismaux - Renier de Huy.JPG|thumb|270px|Saint [[John the Baptist]] preaching, the start of the sequence of scenes]]\n[[File:Renier de Huy JPG01.jpg|thumb|270px|The last two scenes]]\n\nThe basin is {{convert|91|cm|in}} across at the top, tapering slightly towards the base, and is  variously described as of [[brass]] or [[bronze]].<ref>The two terms for copper alloys have some overlap.</ref> It was made by [[lost wax]] casting, with the basin cast in a single piece; the size was not necessarily exceptional, as both church bells and cauldrons for large households were probably cast at comparable sizes; some church doors cast in a single piece, though flat, were much larger.  The font sat on twelve oxen (two are now missing), who emerged from a stone [[plinth]], a reference to the \"molten sea... on twelve oxen\" cast in bronze for [[Solomon's temple]]<ref>{{bibleverse|1|Kings|7:23-7:27|NIV}}; this feature is today typical of fonts in [[The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints]].</ref>  The five scenes shown, identified by Latin inscriptions (\"tituli\") on the rim above and in the image field, can be read in chronological sequence:<ref>See the continuous diagram at Xhayet and Halleux, 124; the scenes are covered in great detail in the pages following; also Calkins, 128</ref><ref>{{cite web\n |url         = http://www.st-barthelemy.be/Gifs/graphique_lineaire.gif\n |title       = Linear graphic of Baptismal font at St Bartholomew's  Church (official website)\n |publisher   = ASBL \"Art et Histoire - Saint-Barth\u00e9lemy - Li\u00e8ge\"\n |work        = Picture\n |archiveurl  = https://www.webcitation.org/5mva3yNy3?url=http://www.st-barthelemy.be/Gifs/graphique_lineaire.gif\n |archivedate = 2010-01-20\n |url-status     = dead\n |access-date = 2010-01-20\n}} (in French)</ref>\n\n*[[John the Baptist]] preaching to four figures, the last on the right in full military gear; followed by a [[ficus|fig]] tree.<ref>Xhayet and Halleux, 124-6</ref>\n*John baptising two neophytes, with two further figures to the right, who probably represent the two disciples John told to follow Jesus (John 1:35\u201337).  As often in Early Medieval art, the attempt to convey the [[River Jordan]] stretching away in [[graphical perspective|perspective]] has it rise up like a mound.  A [[Arecaceae|palm]] tree follows.<ref>Xhayet and Halleux, 126-9</ref>\n*The ''[[Baptism of Jesus|Baptism of Christ]]'' by John the Baptist, a commonly represented scene, again with the water piling up like a mound.  Jesus is beardless and young, as is also typical. The angel to the right of Jesus has his hands veiled with a cloth, a mark of respect in Eastern [[liturgy]], though it may also simply represent a cloth ready for Jesus to dry himself with.  An [[olive]] tree follows.<ref>Xhayet and Halleux, 129\u2013131</ref>\n*[[Saint Peter]] baptising  [[Cornelius the Centurion]], the first [[gentile]] to be baptised  ([[Acts]] 10), with a sponsor or godfather.  The [[Hand of God (art)|Hand of God]] appears from above to signal approval.<ref>Xhayet and Halleux, 131-32</ref>\n*Saint [[John the Evangelist]] baptising the \"philosopher [[Craton]]\", also with a sponsor and Hand. A [[vine]] follows.  The story of Craton comes from [[apocryphal]] writings such as the account of John's life by the [[Pseudo-Abdias]].<ref>Cartlidge and Elliott, 195; for a full account in French see Xhayet and Halleux, 199ff, and 132-33.</ref>\n[[File:Fonts baptismaux.jpg|thumb|left|100px|Baptismal font of [[Furnaux]] also inspired by Rupert de Deutz]]\nExcept for the last two the scenes are separated by trees which are stylised in typical Romanesque fashion, but whose leaf shapes are all different.<ref>See the comparison at Xhayet and Halleux, 127, where each is identified as respectively fig, vine, olive and palm.</ref>  A continuous undulating ground-line runs all round the basin.  Other inscriptions run round the top and bottom rims of the basin.<ref>Xhayet and Halleux, 94\u201398 give the texts.  These are a number of [[hexameter]]s of [[Leonine verse]], the upper ones explaining the relief scenes while the lower one explains the oxen: \"By the twelve oxen is shown the ''[[Typology (theology)|forma]]'' [type] of pastors, through the example of whose apostolic life, full of grace, and their elevated office, the citizens are purified, and the spirit of these waters refreshes the holy city\" (approximate translation)</ref>  While the baptism of Jesus is very commonly depicted in Early Medieval art, those of the other figures are very rare subjects indeed,<ref>St Peter baptising an unspecified figure is shown on an ivory book cover of c. 900 in Florence, in a similar composition which also has a layperson to the right of the font, holding textiles (the naked catchumen's clothes, or a towel) which veil his hands in a similar way to the angel in the Baptism of Jesus scene here. Lasko, plate 63</ref> and this unusually elaborate and learned programme was no doubt composed with clerical assistance. It does not reflect Byzantine [[iconographic]] precedents; instead it matches closely the interest in [[typology (theology)|typology]] and [[allegory]], of which the influential contemporary Li\u00e8ge-born theologian [[Rupert of Deutz]] was a particular exponent (though Rupert was also a particular opponent of the bishop at the time, [[Otbert of Li\u00e8ge]], who took the Emperor's side in the [[Investiture Controversy]]).<ref>Xhayet and Halleux, 133, and 122 on their dispute. See also Henderson (1977), 229</ref>  The head of [[God the Father]] that appears at the top of the ''Baptism of Christ'' (identified as <small>PATER</small>) is an early appearance of [[God the Father in Western art]]; a [[Hand of God (art)|Hand of God]], more typical of the period, appears in the baptism scenes of Cornelius and Craton.\n\nThe baptismal font in the little village of [[Furnaux]] ([[Mettet]]), relatively far from [[Li\u00e8ge]] but at that time in the same [[diocese]], has the same theological background linking [[Rupert de Deutz]]'s theological vision where the [[Old Testament]] and [[New Testament]] are closely linked.\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|2}}\n{{Commons category|Baptismal font of Renier de Huy, Li\u00e8ge}}\n\n== References ==\n*Beckwith, John.  ''Early Medieval Art: Carolingian, Ottonian, Romanesque'', Thames & Hudson, 1964 (rev. 1969), {{ISBN|0-500-20019-X}}\n*Calkins, Robert G.; ''Monuments of Medieval Art'', Dutton, 1979, {{ISBN|0-525-47561-3}}\n*Cartlidge, David R. and Elliott, James Keith, ''Art and the Christian Apocrypha'', Routledge, 2001, {{ISBN|0-415-23392-5}}, {{ISBN|978-0-415-23392-7}}, [https://books.google.com/books?id=o0LBvOMYArYC&pg=PA195&dq=John+baptising+the+philosopher+Craton&cd=1#v=onepage&q=&f=false Google books]\n*{{citation|last1=Colman |first1=Pierre  |last2=Lhoist-Colman|first2=Berthe   |title=Les   fonts baptismaux de Saint-Barth\u00e9lemy \u00e0 Li\u00e8ge - Chef-d'oeuvre sans pareil et noeud de   controverses|publisher=Acad\u00e9mie Royale de Belgique|year=2003|isbn=2-8031-0189-0|language=French}}\n*Henderson, George. ''Gothic Art'', 1967, Penguin, {{ISBN|0-14-020806-2}}\n*Henderson, George. ''Early Medieval Art'', 1972, rev. 1977, Penguin.\n*[[Hugh Honour]] and John Fleming, ''A World History of Art'', 1st edn. 1982 & later editions, Macmillan, London, page refs to 1984 Macmillan 1st edn. paperback. {{ISBN|0-333-37185-2}}\n*Kleiner, Fred S., Christin J. Mamiya, and Helen Gardner. ''Gardner's Art Through the Ages''. Belmont: Wadsworth, 2004\n*[[Peter Lasko|Lasko, Peter]], ''Ars Sacra'', Penguin History of Art (now Yale)\n*[https://archive.is/20020221131529/http://www.liege.be/visitelg/tourisme/patrirel/anglais/baptfont.htm#e City of Li\u00e8ge Tourism, with good feature], and a bibliography of recent scholarship in French. Accessed 10 Jan. 2010\n*\"Oxford\": Rainer of Huy: ''The Oxford Dictionary of Art.'' Accessed 10 Jan. 2010, [http://www.enotes.com/oxford-art-encyclopedia/rainer-huy]\n*Swarzenski, Hanns. ''Monuments of Romanesque Art; The Art of Church Treasures in North-Western Europe'', [[Faber and Faber]], 1974, {{ISBN|0-571-10588-2}}\n*Xhayet, Genevi\u00e8ve and Halleux, Robert (eds), ''\u00c9tudes sur les fonts baptismaux de Saint-Barth\u00e9l\u00e9my \u00e0 Li\u00e8ge'', Editions du CEFAL, 2006, {{ISBN|2-87130-212-X}}, 9782871302124 [https://books.google.com/books?id=FBM-v_6uzpwC&pg=PA99&dq=Pierre+Colman,+Les+fonts+baptismaux+de+Saint-Barth%C3%A9lemy&cd=2#v=onepage&q=Pierre%20Colman%2C%20Les%20fonts%20baptismaux%20de%20Saint-Barth%C3%A9lemy&f=false google books]\n\n==External links==\n* {{cite web| url=http://www.kikirpa.be/www2/cgi-bin/wwwopac.exe?DATABASE=fotos2&LANGUAGE=0&COPYTEXT=&COPYRIGHT=&OPAC_URL=&10060034=on| title=Detailed picture gallery of Baptismal font at St Bartholomew's Church of Li\u00e8ge|accessdate=2010-01-20|publisher=Royal Institute for the Study and Conservation of Belgium's Artistic Heritage|work=Picture Library}} (in French)\n* {{cite web| url= http://www.st-barthelemy.be/Galerie_FB/Gal_Tof.htm| title= Picture gallery of Baptismal font at St Bartholomew's  Church (official website)| accessdate= 2010-01-20| publisher= ASBL \"Art et Histoire - Saint-Barth\u00e9lemy - Li\u00e8ge\"| work= Picture  Library| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100113133432/http://www.st-barthelemy.be/Galerie_FB/Gal_Tof.htm| archivedate= 2010-01-13| url-status= dead}} (in French)\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Baptismal Font At St Bartholomew's Church, Liege}}\n[[Category:Baptismal fonts]]\n[[Category:Bronze sculptures in Belgium]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic churches in Li\u00e8ge|*]]\n[[Category:History of Li\u00e8ge]]\n[[Category:Medieval European sculptures]]\n[[Category:Mosan art]]\n[[Category:Walloon culture]]\n[[Category:Medieval European metalwork objects]]\n", "name_user": "Dominikmatus", "label": "safe", "comment": "+ reference", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Baptismal_font_at_St_Bartholomew%27s_Church,_Li%C3%A8ge"}
{"title_page": "Shaw Academy", "text_new": "{{short description|Online education organisation in Dublin, Ireland}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{advert|date=January 2019}}\n{{COI|date=August 2019}}\n{{POV|date=February 2020}}\n}}\n{{Infobox website\n| name = Shaw Academy\n| logo = ShawAcademylogo.png\n| type = [[E-learning|Online learning]]\n| language = [[English language|English]]\n| founder = {{ubl|James Egan|Adrian Murphy}}\n| url = {{url|shawacademy.com}}\n| launch_date = 2013\n}}\n\n'''Shaw Academy''' is a privately owned [[online education]] organisation based in [[Dublin]], Ireland.<ref name=\"financialtimes\">{{cite web | url = https://www.ft.com/content/1f3b2402-cb3b-11e5-a8ef-ea66e967dd44 | title = Edtech providers move from Moocs to social networking | last = Moules | first = Jonathan | date = 7 March 2016 | publisher = [[Financial Times]]}}</ref><ref name=\"huffingtonpost\">{{cite web | url = http://www.huffingtonpost.com/jonha-revesencio/a-look-at-coursera-the-sh_b_7095034.html | title = A Look at Coursera, The Shaw Academy and Lynda.com: Which One Stands Out? | last = Revesencio | first = Jonha | date = 19 June 2015 | website = [[The Huffington Post]] |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150422001007/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/jonha-revesencio/a-look-at-coursera-the-sh_b_7095034.html | archivedate = 22 April 2015 }}</ref>\n\nFounded in 2013, Shaw Academy provides online courses which are audio/video recorded and deliver them to students through scheduled webinar times decided by the student to suit their \"own pace\".<ref name=\"huffingtonpost\"/> The courses offered cover subjects including photography, health and fitness, financial trading, nutrition, web development, mobile app development and digital marketing.<ref name=\"irishtimesedu\">{{cite web | url = http://www.irishtimes.com/news/education/we-don-t-need-no-free-market-education-1.2539969 | title = We don\u2019t need no free-market education | last = O'Brien | first = Stephen | date = 23 February 2016 | website = [[The Irish Times]] }}</ref><ref name=\"europapress\">{{cite web | url = http://www.europapress.es/campusvivo/cursos-masteres/noticia-shaw-academy-lanza-cursos-gratis-marketing-financial-trading-fotografia-nutricion-20150904135152.html | title = ACCESS THROUGH LIVE CAMPUS | access-date = 22 September 2015 | publisher = [[Europa Press (news agency)|Europa Press]]}}</ref> Shaw Academy uses online tools to answer students' live questions.<ref name=\"huffingtonpost\" />\n\nThe Shaw Academy has over 6.5 million students from its courses and professional diplomas spread across the world. Courses are built around a series of Interactive Online Classes focusing on practical knowledge coupled with peer-interaction and student support. Built to be convenient and flexible, students can schedule and reschedule classes at ease and can even catch up on classes on the go - ensuring they can learn at their own pace without wasting any of their valuable time. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fenews.co.uk/press-releases/44829-online-education-platform-shaw-academy-offers-free-courses-in-areas-affected-by-coronavirus|title=Online education platform Shaw Academy offers free courses in areas affected by Coronavirus|last=Academy|first=Shaw|website=FE News|language=en-gb|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nShaw Academy was founded by James Egan and Adrian Murphy in 2013.<ref name = \"siliconrepublic\">{{cite web | url = https://www.siliconrepublic.com/careers/2016/01/29/40-jobs-dublin-shaw-academy | title = 40 jobs in Dublin at online learning company Shaw Academy | last = Hunt | first = Gordon | date = 29 January 2016 | website = Silicon Republic }}</ref>\n\nBy January 2016, Shaw Academy was teaching about 55,000 new students each month.<ref name = \"irishtimesjobs\">{{cite web | url = http://www.irishtimes.com/business/technology/shaw-academy-to-create-40-jobs-in-dublin-1.2515720 | title = Shaw Academy to create 40 jobs in Dublin | last = O'Brien | first = Ciara | date = 29 January 2016 | website = [[The Irish Times]] }}</ref> By November of that year, it was teaching 400,000 new students every month and had surpassed teaching over 1.84 million students.<ref name = \"businessworld\">{{cite web | url = http://bwdisrupt.businessworld.in/article/Flipkart-and-Shaw-Academy-Bring-Live-Education-to-the-Indian-Online-Marketplace/21-11-2016-108568/ | title = Flipkart and Shaw Academy Bring Live Education to the Indian Online Marketplace | date = 21 November 2016 | website = [[Businessworld]] }}</ref><ref name = \"inc42\">{{cite web | url = https://inc42.com/flash-feed/flipkart-forays-online-learning/ | title = Flipkart Forays Into Online Learning; Partners With Shaw Academy | last = Agarwal | first = Meha | date = 18 November 2016 | website = Inc42 }}</ref>\n\nIn January 2016, founder Adrian Murphy and Irish Minister for Jobs, Richard Bruton, announced 40 new education positions in the Dublin office.<ref name = \"siliconrepublic\" /><ref name = \"irishtimesjobs\" /><ref name = \"enterpriseireland\">{{cite web | url = http://newsletter.enterprise-ireland.com/1xnwjm1a27g?a=1&p=49805714&t=28830144 | title = 40 jobs in Dublin at online learning company Shaw Academy | website = [[Enterprise Ireland]] | access-date = 4 February 2016 }}</ref> The CEO of Irish government agency [[Enterprise Ireland]], Julie Sinnamon, described Shaw Academy at the time as \"an example of an innovative Irish company in the growing online learning market, who are also supporting other Irish SMEs to grow through their extensive suite of online courses.\"<ref name = \"siliconrepublic\" /><ref name = \"enterpriseireland\" />\n\nIn January 2017, Shaw Academy launched an educational platform, called Phoenix, to accommodate growing student numbers. Phoenix is marketed as a tool to enable Shaw Academy to teach more students live online simultaneously whilst also providing an automated yet personalised service to its students.<ref name = \"insightssuccess\">{{cite web | url = http://www.insightssuccess.com/shaw-academy-launches-a-new-education-technology-platform/ | title = Shaw Academy launches a new Education Technology Platform | website = insightssuccess.com | access-date = 31 January 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2019, despite having sold courses to 4.5m students and a revenue the previous year of \u20ac7.2m, the organisation ran into financial difficulties with the calling in of a \u20ac5.7m debt resulting in the High Court appointing an insolvency practitioner.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/harsh-lesson-for-dublin-online-education-firm-shaw-academy-as-it-falls-from-top-of-class-kbz5wx0tv|title=Harsh lesson for Dublin online education firm Shaw Academy as it falls from top of class|first=Philip|last=Connolly|via=www.thetimes.co.uk|url-status=live|url-access=subscription}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.ie/business/irish/examiner-picks-six-bidders-for-shaw-academy-37800012.html|title=Examiner picks six bidders for Shaw Academy|website=independent}}</ref>  Shaw Academy secured \u20ac7 million in funding in April 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.prnewswire.co.uk/news-releases/shaw-academy-secures-eur7-000-000-investment-and-successfully-exits-examinership-831718695.html|title=Shaw Academy Secures \u20ac7,000,000+ Investment and Successfully Exits Examinership|first=Shaw|last=Academy|website=www.prnewswire.co.uk}}</ref>{{better source|date=February 2020}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/business/technology/shaw-academy-to-exit-examinership-with-7m-investment-1.3844655|title=Shaw Academy to exit examinership with \u20ac7m investment|first=Peter|last=Hamilton|website=The Irish Times}}</ref>\n\n== Courses ==\nShaw Academy offers courses ranging from business related topics such as digital marketing, social media marketing and web development to wellness programmes such as health and fitness and sports nutrition.<ref name = \"inc42\" /> Courses are delivered with recordings of live presentations.<ref name = \"inc42\" /><ref name = \"indiainfoline\" /> Students can log on to an online portal to complete assignments, exams, review modules, replay lectures, and view additional content. Educational and technical support teams are also available to students.<ref name = \"huffingtonpost\" /><ref name = \"inc\">{{cite web | url = http://www.inc.com/aj-agrawal/5-reasons-why-online-learning-is-the-future-of-education.html | title = 5 Benefits That Make Online Learning With Shaw Academy the Future of Education | last = Agrawal | first = AJ | publisher = [[Inc. (magazine)|Inc.com]] | access-date = 30 September 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Partners==\nShaw Academy has reportedly formed partnerships with companies in e-commerce, telecom and recruitment sector such as [[Adobe Systems|Adobe]], [[GoDaddy]] and [[Naukri.com]].<ref name = \"businessworld\" /><ref name=\"yahoofinancedec16\">{{cite web | url = http://finance.yahoo.com/news/shaw-academy-reaches-another-milestone-130000045.html | title = Shaw Academy Reaches Another Milestone | date = 9 December 2016 | website = [[Yahoo! Finance]] }}</ref>\n\nIn November 2016, Shaw Academy partnered with Indian e-commerce marketplace [[Flipkart]] to provide certified courses on its portal.<ref name = \"businessworld\" /><ref name = \"industryandbusiness\">{{cite web | url = http://www.industryandbusiness.ie/india-trade-mission-sees-partnerships-signed/ | title = India Trade Mission Sees Partnerships Signed | date = 22 November 2016 | website = Industry and Business }}</ref>\n\n== Office locations ==\nThe company's headquarters are in Dublin, Ireland, and it has other offices elsewhere, employing approximately 200 staff globally.<ref name = \"siliconrepublic\" /><ref name = \"irishtimesjobs\" />\n\nIn September 2015, Shaw Academy set up an office in [[Bangalore]], India, which employs over 120 staff.<ref name = \"indiainfoline\">{{cite web | url = http://www.indiainfoline.com/article/b-school-news/flipkart-partners-with-shaw-academy-to-bring-live-education-to-indian-online-marketplace-116111800328_1.html | title = Flipkart partners with Shaw Academy to bring live education to Indian online marketplace | date = 18 November 2016 | website = [[India Infoline]] }}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{Official Website|http://www.shawacademy.com/}}\n\n[[Category:Irish educational websites]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Online education organisation in Dublin, Ireland}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{advert|date=January 2019}}\n{{COI|date=August 2019}}\n{{POV|date=February 2020}}\n}}\n{{Infobox website\n| name = Shaw Academy\n| logo = ShawAcademylogo.png\n| type = [[E-learning|Online learning]]\n| language = [[English language|English]]\n| founder = {{ubl|James Egan|Adrian Murphy}}\n| url = {{url|shawacademy.com}}\n| launch_date = 2013\n}}\n\n'''Shaw Academy''' is a privately owned [[online education]] organisation based in [[Dublin]], Ireland.<ref name=\"financialtimes\">{{cite web | url = https://www.ft.com/content/1f3b2402-cb3b-11e5-a8ef-ea66e967dd44 | title = Edtech providers move from Moocs to social networking | last = Moules | first = Jonathan | date = 7 March 2016 | publisher = [[Financial Times]]}}</ref><ref name=\"huffingtonpost\">{{cite web | url = http://www.huffingtonpost.com/jonha-revesencio/a-look-at-coursera-the-sh_b_7095034.html | title = A Look at Coursera, The Shaw Academy and Lynda.com: Which One Stands Out? | last = Revesencio | first = Jonha | date = 19 June 2015 | website = [[The Huffington Post]] |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150422001007/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/jonha-revesencio/a-look-at-coursera-the-sh_b_7095034.html | archivedate = 22 April 2015 }}</ref>\n\nFounded in 2013, Shaw Academy provides online courses which are audio/video recorded and deliver them to students through scheduled webinar times decided by the student to suit their \"own pace\".<ref name=\"huffingtonpost\"/> The courses offered