Live Education to the Indian Online Marketplace | date = 21 November 2016 | website = [[Businessworld]] }}</ref><ref name = \"inc42\">{{cite web | url = https://inc42.com/flash-feed/flipkart-forays-online-learning/ | title = Flipkart Forays Into Online Learning; Partners With Shaw Academy | last = Agarwal | first = Meha | date = 18 November 2016 | website = Inc42 }}</ref>\n\nIn January 2016, founder Adrian Murphy and Irish Minister for Jobs, Richard Bruton, announced 40 new education positions in the Dublin office.<ref name = \"siliconrepublic\" /><ref name = \"irishtimesjobs\" /><ref name = \"enterpriseireland\">{{cite web | url = http://newsletter.enterprise-ireland.com/1xnwjm1a27g?a=1&p=49805714&t=28830144 | title = 40 jobs in Dublin at online learning company Shaw Academy | website = [[Enterprise Ireland]] | access-date = 4 February 2016 }}</ref> The CEO of Irish government agency [[Enterprise Ireland]], Julie Sinnamon, described Shaw Academy at the time as \"an example of an innovative Irish company in the growing online learning market, who are also supporting other Irish SMEs to grow through their extensive suite of online courses.\"<ref name = \"siliconrepublic\" /><ref name = \"enterpriseireland\" />\n\nIn January 2017, Shaw Academy launched an educational platform, called Phoenix, to accommodate growing student numbers. Phoenix is marketed as a tool to enable Shaw Academy to teach more students live online simultaneously whilst also providing an automated yet personalised service to its students.<ref name = \"insightssuccess\">{{cite web | url = http://www.insightssuccess.com/shaw-academy-launches-a-new-education-technology-platform/ | title = Shaw Academy launches a new Education Technology Platform | website = insightssuccess.com | access-date = 31 January 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2019, despite having sold courses to 4.5m students and a revenue the previous year of \u20ac7.2m, the organisation ran into financial difficulties with the calling in of a \u