-online-learning-is-the-future-of-education.html | title = 5 Benefits That Make Online Learning With Shaw Academy the Future of Education | last = Agrawal | first = AJ | publisher = [[Inc. (magazine)|Inc.com]] | access-date = 30 September 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Partners==\nShaw Academy has reportedly formed partnerships with companies in e-commerce, telecom and recruitment sector such as [[Adobe Systems|Adobe]], [[GoDaddy]] and [[Naukri.com]].<ref name = \"businessworld\" /><ref name=\"yahoofinancedec16\">{{cite web | url = http://finance.yahoo.com/news/shaw-academy-reaches-another-milestone-130000045.html | title = Shaw Academy Reaches Another Milestone | date = 9 December 2016 | website = [[Yahoo! Finance]] }}</ref>\n\nIn November 2016, Shaw Academy partnered with Indian e-commerce marketplace [[Flipkart]] to provide certified courses on its portal.<ref name = \"businessworld\" /><ref name = \"industryandbusiness\">{{cite web | url = http://www.industryandbusiness.ie/india-trade-mission-sees-partnerships-signed/ | title = India Trade Mission Sees Partnerships Signed | date = 22 November 2016 | website = Industry and Business }}</ref>\n\n== Office locations ==\nThe company's headquarters are in Dublin, Ireland, and it has other offices elsewhere, employing approximately 200 staff globally.<ref name = \"siliconrepublic\" /><ref name = \"irishtimesjobs\" />\n\nIn September 2015, Shaw Academy set up an office in [[Bangalore]], India, which employs over 120 staff.<ref name = \"indiainfoline\">{{cite web | url = http://www.indiainfoline.com/article/b-school-news/flipkart-partners-with-shaw-academy-to-bring-live-education-to-indian-online-marketplace-116111800328_1.html | title = Flipkart partners with Shaw Academy to bring live education to Indian online marketplace | date = 18 November 2016 | website = [[India Infoline]] }}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{Official Website|http://www.shawacademy.com/}}\n\n[[Category:Irish educational websites]]\n", "name_user": "Shaw Fitzwilliam", "label": "safe", "comment": "Rectifying minor edit.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shaw_Academy"}
{"title_page": "List of PowerPC processors", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\nThe following is a '''list of PowerPC processors'''.\n\n== General-purpose PowerPC processors ==\n\n=== IBM/Motorola ===\n\n==== [[PowerPC 600|PowerPC 600 family]] ====\n* [[PowerPC 600#PowerPC 601|601]] 50 and 66&nbsp;MHz\n* [[PowerPC 600#PowerPC 602|602]] consumer products (multiplexed data/address bus)\n* [[PowerPC 600#PowerPC 603|603]]/[[PowerPC 600#PowerPC 603|603e]]/[[PowerPC 600#PowerPC 603|603ev]] notebooks, embedded devices\n* [[PowerPC 600#PowerPC 604|604]]/[[PowerPC 600#PowerPC 604e|604e]]/[[PowerPC 600#PowerPC 604e|604ev]] workstations and low end servers\n* [[PowerPC 600#PowerPC 620|620]] the first 64-bit implementation\n\n==== [[PowerPC 7xx|PowerPC 7xx family]] ====\n* 740/750 (1997) 233\u2013366&nbsp;MHz\n\n=== Motorola/Freescale ===\n\n==== PowerPC 7xx family ====\n* [[PowerPC 750|PowerPC 740 and 750]], 233-366&nbsp;MHz\n* [[PowerPC 7xx|745/755]], 300\u2013466&nbsp;MHz\n\n==== PowerPC 74xx family ====\n* 7400/7410 350 - 550&nbsp;MHz, uses [[AltiVec]], a [[SIMD]] extension of the original PPC specs\n* 7440/7450 micro-architecture family up to 1.5&nbsp;GHz and 256 kB on-chip L2 cache and improved Altivec\n* 7447/7457 micro-architecture family up to 1.83&nbsp;GHz with 512 kB on-chip L2 cache\n* 7448 micro-architecture family (2.0&nbsp;GHz) in 90&nbsp;nm with 1MB L2 cache and slightly improved AltiVec (out of order instructions).\n*8640/8641/8640D/8641D with one or two e600 cores, 1MB L2 cache\n\n=== IBM ===\n\n==== [[IBM POWER microprocessors]] ====\n* [[POWER3]], 64-bit, 200 - 450&nbsp;MHz (as POWER3-II), originally the PowerPC 630. Introduced in 1998.\n* [[POWER4]], 64-bit, dual core, 1.0 - 1.9&nbsp;GHz (as POWER4+), follows the PowerPC 2.00 ISA. Introduced in 2001.\n* [[POWER5]], 64-bit, dual core, 2 way [[Simultaneous multithreading|SMT]]/core, 1.6 - 2.0&nbsp;GHz, follows the PowerPC 2.01 ISA. Introduced in 2004.\n* [[POWER5#POWER5+|POWER5+]], 64-bit, dual core, 2 way SMT/core, 1.9 - 2.2&nbsp;GHz, follows the PowerPC 2.02 ISA. Introduced in 2005.\n* [[POWER6]], 64-bit, dual core, 2 way SMT/core, 3.6 \u2013 4.7&nbsp;GHz, follows the Power ISA 2.03. Introduced in 2007.\n* [[POWER6#POWER6+|POWER6+]], 64 bit, dual core, 2 way SMT/core, 5.0&nbsp;GHz, follows the Power ISA 2.05. Introduced in 2009.\n* [[POWER7]], 64-bit octo core, 4 way SMT/core, 2.4-4.25&nbsp;GHz, follows the Power ISA 2.06. Introduced in 2010.\n* [[POWER7#POWER7+|POWER7+]], 64-bit octo core, 4 way SMT/core, 3.0-5.0&nbsp;GHz, follows the Power ISA 2.06. Introduced in 2012.\n* [[POWER8]], 64-bit, hex or twelve core, 8 way SMT/core, 5.0&nbsp;GHz, follows the Power ISA 2.07. Introduced in 2014.\n\n==== [[RS64]] ====\n* A10 (Cobra), 50-77&nbsp;MHz, 1995, single chip processor for Series i\n* A25/30 (Muskie), 125-154&nbsp;MHz, 1996, multi chip, 4 way SMP for Series i\n* RS64 (Apache), 64-bit, 125&nbsp;MHz, 1997 for large scale SMP systems Series i and Series p\n* RS64-II (Northstar),  262&nbsp;MHz, 1998\n* RS64-III (Pulsar, Istar),  450&nbsp;MHz in 1999, 600 in 2000\n* RS64-IV (Sstar), 750&nbsp;MHz, multithreading, 2000\n\n==== PowerPC 7xx family ====\n* [[PowerPC 7xx|750CL]] with 256 kB on die L2 cache at 400-900&nbsp;MHz introduced in 2006\n* [[PowerPC 7xx|750CX/CXe]] with 256 kB on die L2 cache at 350-600&nbsp;MHz\n* [[PowerPC 7xx|750FX]] with 512 kB L2 cache announced by IBM in 2001 and available early 2002 at 1&nbsp;GHz\n* [[PowerPC 7xx|750GX]] with 1 MB L2 cache introduced by IBM in 2003\n\n==== [[PowerPC 970|PowerPC 970 family]] ====\n* 970 (2003), 64-bit, derived from [[POWER4]], enhanced with [[AltiVec|VMX]], 512 kB L2 cache, 1.4 \u2013 2&nbsp;GHz\n* 970FX (2004), manufactured at [[90 nanometer|90 nm]], 1.8 - 2.7&nbsp;GHz\n* 970GX (2006), manufactured at [[90 nanometer|90 nm]], 1MB L2 cache/core, 1.2 - 2.5&nbsp;GHz\n* 970MP (2005), dual core, 1 MB L2 cache/core, 1.6 - 2.5&nbsp;GHz\n\n==== [[Cell microprocessor|Cell]] ====\n* [[Cell microprocessor|Cell BE]], 64-bit [[Cell (microprocessor)#Power Processor Element .28PPE.29|PPE-core]], 2 way multithreading, VMX, 512 kB L2 cache, 8x SPE, 8x 256 kB Local Store memory, 3.2&nbsp;GHz, follows the PowerPC 2.02 ISA\n* Cell BE 65&nbsp;nm, same as above but manufactured on a 65&nbsp;nm process\n* PowerXCell 8i, same as above but with enhanced double precision SPEs and support for DDR-RAM\n\n==== Supercomputer ====\n* [[Blue Gene/L]], dual core PowerPC 440, 700&nbsp;MHz, 2004\n* [[Blue Gene/P]], quad core PowerPC 450, 850&nbsp;MHz, 2007\n* [[Blue Gene/Q]], 18 core PowerPC A2, 1.6&nbsp;GHz, 2011\n\n=== Other ===\n* [[Exponential Technology]] [[x704]], a [[BiCMOS]] PowerPC implementation, 410 to 533&nbsp;MHz\n* [[P.A. Semi]] [[PWRficient]] PA6T-1682M, a dual-core microprocessor that runs at 2&nbsp;GHz\n\n== Embedded PowerPC ==\n\n32-bit and 64-bit PowerPC processors have been a favorite of embedded computer designers. To keep costs low on high-volume competitive products, the CPU core is usually bundled into a system-on-chip (SOC) integrated circuit. SOCs contain the processor core, cache and the processor's local data on-chip, along with clocking, timers, memory (SDRAM), peripheral (network, serial I/O), and bus (PCI, PCI-X, ROM/Flash bus, I2C) controllers. IBM also offers an open bus architecture (called [[CoreConnect]]) to facilitate connection of the processor core to memory and peripherals in a SOC design.  IBM and Motorola have competed along parallel development lines in overlapping markets. A later development was the [http://www.nxp.com/docs/en/user-guide/BOOK_EUM.pdf Book E PowerPC Specification], implemented by both IBM and Freescale Semiconductor, which defines embedded extensions to the PowerPC programming model.\n\n===AMCC===\n* [[PowerPC 400#PowerPC 440|440SP]]: 533-667&nbsp;MHz, 10/100/1G Ethernet, (2) 64bit PCI-X, 32bit PCI-X, XOR engine, 32k L1 Cache.\n* [[PowerPC 400#PowerPC 440|440SPe]]: 533-667&nbsp;MHz, 10/100/1G Ethernet, (3) 64bit PCI-Express, 64bit PCI-X, XOR engine, 32k L1 Cache.\n* [[PowerPC 400#PowerPC 440|440EPx]]: 333-667&nbsp;MHz, (2) 10/100/1G Ethernet, Hardware Security, PCI, DDR-II, FPU, USB 1.1 or USB 2.0, 32k L1 Cache.\n* [[PowerPC 400#PowerPC 440|440GR]]: 333-667&nbsp;MHz, (2) 10/100 Ethernet, (4) UART, (2) IIC, 53 GPIO, SPI, 32k L1 Cache.\n* [[PowerPC 400#PowerPC 440|440GRx]]: 333-667&nbsp;MHz, (2) 10/100/1G Ethernet, (4) UART, (2) IIC, 53 GPIO, SPI, DDR-II, Hardware Security, 32k L1 Cache.\n* PowerPC [[Titan (microprocessor)|Titan]], 32-bit, dual core, 2&nbsp;GHz. Announced, planned release in 2008\n\n===Broad Reach Engineering===\n* [[BRE440]] [[radiation hardened]] CPU based on [[PowerPC 440#PowerPC 440|PowerPC 440]] core with 256 kB L2 Cache, PCI, (2) 10/100 Ethernet, 4-CH DMA, (2) UART, extensive on chip memory control. Designed specifically for radiation environments and extreme temperature environments (such as space).\n\n===BAE Systems===\n* [[RAD750]] [[radiation hardened]] CPU based on [[PowerPC 750]] core.\n\n===Culturecom===\n* [[PowerPC 400#V-Dragon|V-Dragon]] based on [[PowerPC 400#PowerPC 405|PowerPC 405]] core.\n\n=== Cray ===\n* SeaStar, SeaStar2 and SeaStar2+, [[PowerPC 400#PowerPC 440|PowerPC 440]] based communications processors for their [[Opteron]] based [[Cray XT3|XT3]], [[Cray XT4|XT4]] and [[Cray XT5|XT5]] supercomputers.\n\n===Freescale (former Motorola)===\n* MPC8xx [[PowerQUICC#PowerQUICC I|PowerQUICC]] - networking & telecom card controllers with embedded communications module, up to 80&nbsp;MHz\n* [[MPC5xx]] - automotive & industrial controllers\n* [[PowerPC 5000#MPC51xx|MPC51xx]]/[[PowerPC 5000#MPC52xx|MPC52xx]] - [[PowerPC e300|e300]] core, automotive & industrial [[system on a chip]] (SoC) controllers, up to 466&nbsp;MHz\n* [[PowerPC 5000#MPC55xx|MPC55xx]] -  [[PowerPC e200|e200]] core, automotive & industrial controllers, up to 144&nbsp;MHz\n* [[PowerPC 5000#MPC56xx|MPC56xx]] -  [[PowerPC e200|e200]] core, automotive & industrial controllers, up to 264&nbsp;MHz\n* MPC82xx [[PowerQUICC#PowerQUICC II|PowerQUICC II]] - [[PowerPC 600#PowerPC 603|603e]] core, networking & telecom SoC controllers with high-capacity on-chip switched bus and communications module, up to 450&nbsp;MHz\n* MPC83xx [[PowerQUICC#PowerQUICC II Pro|PowerQUICC II Pro]] - [[PowerPC e300|e300]] core, networking & telecom SoC controllers with high-capacity on-chip switched bus and communications module, up to 667&nbsp;MHz\n* MPC85xx [[PowerQUICC#PowerQUICC III|PowerQUICC III]] - [[PowerPC e500|e500]] core, high end networking & telecom SoC controllers with high-capacity on-chip switched bus and communications module. D Dual core versions supporting both symmetric and asymmetric multiprocessing, up to 1.5&nbsp;GHz.\n* MPC864x - [[PowerPC e600|e600]] core, 1 MB L2 cache, improved [[AltiVec]] (out of order instructions), an embedded memory controller, Ethernet controllers, a [[RapidIO]] fabric interface, a [[PCI Express]] interface, and MPX bus. Dual core versions supporting both symmetric and asymmetric multiprocessing, up to 1.5&nbsp;GHz.\n* [[QorIQ]] Processing Platforms (evolution of the [[PowerQUICC]]). The first letter of the model indicates the series, the second and the third model number indicates the number of cores (e.g. P5040 has four cores, T4240 has 24 cores)\n** [[QorIQ#P Series|P series]]\n*** [[QorIQ#P1|P1 series]], [[PowerPC e500#e500v2|e500v2 cores]]: P1011, P1020\n*** [[QorIQ#P2|P2 series]]: [[PowerPC e500#e500v2|e500v2 core]] P2020, [[PowerPC e500#e500mc|e500mc cores]] P2040, P2041\n*** [[QorIQ#P3|P3 series]], introduced in 2010, based on [[PowerPC e500#e500mc|e500mc cores]]: P3041\n*** [[QorIQ#P4|P4 series]], introduced in 2009, based on [[PowerPC e500#e500mc|e500mc cores]]: P4080\n*** [[QorIQ#P5|P5 series]], introduced in 2012, 45&nbsp;nm process, based on [[PowerPC e5500|e5500 cores]]: P5010, P5020, P5021, P5040\n** [[QorIQ#AMP Series|T series]], introduced in 2013, all based on [[PowerPC e6500|e6500 cores]], and 28&nbsp;nm process\n*** [[QorIQ#T1|T1 series]]: T1040, T1042, T1020, T1022\n*** [[QorIQ#T2|T2 series]]: T2080, T2081\n*** [[QorIQ#T4|T4 series]]: T4240, T4160, T4080\n\n===IBM (now from AMCC)===\n* [[PowerPC 400#PowerPC 401|401]]\n* [[PowerPC 400#PowerPC 403|403]]: MMU added in most advanced version 403GCX\n* [[PowerPC 400#PowerPC 405|405]]: MMU, Ethernet, serial, PCI, SRAM, SDRAM; NPe405 adds more network devices\n* [[PowerPC 400#PowerPC 440|440]]: A range of processors based on the Book E core.\n** [[PowerPC 400#PowerPC 440|440EP]]: 333-667&nbsp;MHz, (2) 10/100 Ethernet, PCI, DDR, FPU, USB 1.1 or USB 2.0, 32k L1 Cache.\n** [[PowerPC 400#PowerPC 440|440GP]]: 400-500&nbsp;MHz, (2) 10/100 Ethernet, PCI-X, DDR, 32k L1 Cache.\n** [[PowerPC 400#PowerPC 440|440GX]]: 533-800&nbsp;MHz, (2) 10/100 Ethernet, (2) 10/100/1G Ethernet with TCP/IP hardware acceleration, PCI-X, DDR, 32k L1 Cache\n\n===Microsoft===\n*[[Xenon (processor)|Xenon]] (Microsoft Xbox 360) - Three core [[Power Processing Element|PPE]]-based, 1 MB shared L2 cache, [[Altivec|VMX128]], 3.2&nbsp;GHz\n\n===Nintendo===\n*[[Gekko (microprocessor)|Gekko]] (GameCube) - 750CXe core with special enhancements, 485&nbsp;MHz\n*[[Broadway (microprocessor)|Broadway]] (Wii) - 750CL, 729&nbsp;MHz\n*[[Espresso (microprocessor)|Espresso]] (Wii U) - 3\u00d7 750 cores, 1.24&nbsp;GHz\n\n=== P.A. Semi ===\n* [[PWRficient]] PA6T-1682M: a dual core PPC running at 2&nbsp;GHz\n\n=== Rapport ===\n\n*[[Kilocore]] 1025: a CPU with a single PowerPC core and 1024 processing element (8 bit, 125&nbsp;MHz) cores (unreleased). This CPU is designed for running security and multimedia applications (with parallel processing) on portable game devices and media players.\n\n=== Xilinx ===\n* Some Virtex-II Pro and Virtex-4 [[FPGA]] have up to two embedded [[PowerPC 400#PowerPC 405|PowerPC 405]] cores,.<ref>[http://direct.xilinx.com/bvdocs/publications/ds083.pdf Virtex-II Pro datasheet] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061025211704/http://direct.xilinx.com/bvdocs/publications/ds083.pdf |date=2006-10-25 }}</ref><ref>[http://direct.xilinx.com/bvdocs/publications/ds112.pdf Virtex-4 family overview] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061015234646/http://direct.xilinx.com/bvdocs/publications/ds112.pdf |date=2006-10-15 }}</ref>\n* Virtex-5 FXT has up to two embedded PowerPC 440 cores.\n\n==Northbridge==\n[[Northbridge (computing)|Northbridge]] or host bridge for PowerPC CPU is an [[Integrated Circuit]] (IC) for interfacing PowerPC CPU with memory, and Southbridge IC. Some Northbridge also provide interface for [[Accelerated Graphics Port]]s (AGP) bus, [[Peripheral Component Interconnect]] (PCI), PCI-X, PCI Express, or [[Hypertransport]] bus. Specific Northbridge IC must be used for PowerPC CPU. It is impossible to use Northbridge for Intel or AMD x86 CPU with PowerPC CPU. However it is possible to use certain types of x86 [[Southbridge (computing)|Southbridge]] in PowerPC based motherboards. Example: [[VIA Technologies|VIA]] 686B and [[AMD]] Geode CS5536.\n\nList of Northbridge for PowerPC:\n*IBM:\n**CPC 700 and CPC 710 for IBM PowerPC 750 series.\n**CPC 925 and CPC 945 for IBM PowerPC 970 series.\n*Motorola (now available from Tundra):\n**MPC-105\n**MPC-106\n**MPC-107\n*Mentor Arc Inc. (MAI).\n**Articia S.\n*[[Marvell Technology Group|Marvell]] Discovery series for Motorola MPC74xx and MPC75x and IBM 750 series CPU.\n**Discovery ( GT-64260A, GT-64261A and GT-64262A).\n**Discovery LT (MV64420 and MV64430).\n**Discovery II (MV64360, MV6361 and MV6362).\n**Discovery III (MV64460, MV6461 and MV6462).\n**Discovery V (MV 64560).\n**Discovery VI(MV 64660).\n*Philips Semiconductor\n**VAS96011 and VAS96012: Two IC northbridge for PowerPC 603 and PowerPC 604.\n*Tundra (Canada)\n**TSI-106 (formerly Motorola MPC-106).\n**TSI-107 (formerly Motorola MPC-107) / XPC107APX series.\n**TSI-108\n**TSI-109\n**TSI-110\n**Qspan II - PCI bus interface for PowerPC CPU.\n**PowerPro (CA91L750) - Memory controller for PowerPC CPU.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Lists of microprocessors|PowerPC processors]]\n[[Category:PowerPC microprocessors|*]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\nThe following is a '''list of PowerPC processors'''.\n\n== General-purpose PowerPC processors ==\n\n=== IBM/Motorola ===\n\n==== [[PowerPC 600|PowerPC 600 family]] ====\n* [[PowerPC 600#PowerPC 601|601]] 50 and 66&nbsp;MHz\n* [[PowerPC 600#PowerPC 602|602]] consumer products (multiplexed data/address bus)\n* [[PowerPC 600#PowerPC 603|603]]/[[PowerPC 600#PowerPC 603|603e]]/[[PowerPC 600#PowerPC 603|603ev]] notebooks, embedded devices\n* [[PowerPC 600#PowerPC 604|604]]/[[PowerPC 600#PowerPC 604e|604e]]/[[PowerPC 600#PowerPC 604e|604ev]] workstations and low end servers\n* [[PowerPC 600#PowerPC 620|620]] the first 64-bit implementation\n\n==== [[PowerPC 7xx|PowerPC 7xx family]] ====\n* 740/750 (1997) 233\u2013366&nbsp;MHz\n\n=== Motorola/Freescale ===\n\n==== PowerPC 7xx family ====\n* [[PowerPC 750|PowerPC 740 and 750]], 233-366&nbsp;MHz\n* [[PowerPC 7xx|745/755]], 300\u2013466&nbsp;MHz\n\n==== PowerPC 74xx family ====\n* 7400/7410 350 - 550&nbsp;MHz, uses [[AltiVec]], a [[SIMD]] extension of the original PPC specs\n* 7440/7450 micro-architecture family up to 1.5&nbsp;GHz and 256 kB on-chip L2 cache and improved Altivec\n* 7447/7457 micro-architecture family up to 1.83&nbsp;GHz with 512 kB on-chip L2 cache\n* 7448 micro-architecture family (2.0&nbsp;GHz) in 90&nbsp;nm with 1MB L2 cache and slightly improved AltiVec (out of order instructions).\n*8640/8641/8640D/8641D with one or two e600 cores, 1MB L2 cache\n\n=== IBM ===\n\n==== [[IBM POWER microprocessors]] ====\n* [[POWER3]], 64-bit, 200 - 450&nbsp;MHz (as POWER3-II), originally the PowerPC 630. Introduced in 1998.\n* [[POWER4]], 64-bit, dual core, 1.0 - 1.9&nbsp;GHz (as POWER4+), follows the PowerPC 2.00 ISA. Introduced in 2001.\n* [[POWER5]], 64-bit, dual core, 2 way [[Simultaneous multithreading|SMT]]/core, 1.6 - 2.0&nbsp;GHz, follows the PowerPC 2.01 ISA. Introduced in 2004.\n* [[POWER5#POWER5+|POWER5+]], 64-bit, dual core, 2 way SMT/core, 1.9 - 2.2&nbsp;GHz, follows the PowerPC 2.02 ISA. Introduced in 2005.\n* [[POWER6]], 64-bit, dual core, 2 way SMT/core, 3.6 \u2013 4.7&nbsp;GHz, follows the Power ISA 2.03. Introduced in 2007.\n* [[POWER6#POWER6+|POWER6+]], 64 bit, dual core, 2 way SMT/core, 5.0&nbsp;GHz, follows the Power ISA 2.05. Introduced in 2009.\n* [[POWER7]], 64-bit octo core, 4 way SMT/core, 2.4-4.25&nbsp;GHz, follows the Power ISA 2.06. Introduced in 2010.\n* [[POWER7#POWER7+|POWER7+]], 64-bit octo core, 4 way SMT/core, 3.0-5.0&nbsp;GHz, follows the Power ISA 2.06. Introduced in 2012.\n* [[POWER8]], 64-bit, hex or twelve core, 8 way SMT/core, 5.0&nbsp;GHz, follows the Power ISA 2.07. Introduced in 2014.\n\n==== [[RS64]] ====\n* A10 (Cobra), 50-77&nbsp;MHz, 1995, single chip processor for Series i\n* A25/30 (Muskie), 125-154&nbsp;MHz, 1996, multi chip, 4 way SMP for Series i\n* RS64 (Apache), 64-bit, 125&nbsp;MHz, 1997 for large scale SMP systems Series i and Series p\n* RS64-II (Northstar),  262&nbsp;MHz, 1998\n* RS64-III (Pulsar, Istar),  450&nbsp;MHz in 1999, 600 in 2000\n* RS64-IV (Sstar), 750&nbsp;MHz, multithreading, 2000\n\n==== PowerPC 7xx family ====\n* [[PowerPC 7xx|750CL]] with 256 kB on die L2 cache at 400-900&nbsp;MHz introduced in 2006\n* [[PowerPC 7xx|750CX/CXe]] with 256 kB on die L2 cache at 350-600&nbsp;MHz\n* [[PowerPC 7xx|750FX]] with 512 kB L2 cache announced by IBM in 2001 and available early 2002 at 1&nbsp;GHz\n* [[PowerPC 7xx|750GX]] with 1 MB L2 cache introduced by IBM in 2003\n\n==== [[PowerPC 970|PowerPC 970 family]] ====\n* 970 (2003), 64-bit, derived from [[POWER4]], enhanced with [[AltiVec|VMX]], 512 kB L2 cache, 1.4 \u2013 2&nbsp;GHz\n* 970FX (2004), manufactured at [[90 nanometer|90 nm]], 1.8 - 2.7&nbsp;GHz\n* 970GX (2006), manufactured at [[90 nanometer|90 nm]], 1MB L2 cache/core, 1.2 - 2.5&nbsp;GHz\n* 970MP (2005), dual core, 1 MB L2 cache/core, 1.6 - 2.5&nbsp;GHz\n\n==== [[Cell microprocessor|Cell]] ====\n* [[Cell microprocessor|Cell BE]], 64-bit [[Cell (microprocessor)#Power Processor Element .28PPE.29|PPE-core]], 2 way multithreading, VMX, 512 kB L2 cache, 8x SPE, 8x 256 kB Local Store memory, 3.2&nbsp;GHz, follows the PowerPC 2.02 ISA\n* Cell BE 65&nbsp;nm, same as above but manufactured on a 65&nbsp;nm process\n* PowerXCell 8i, same as above but with enhanced double precision SPEs and support for DDR-RAM\n\n==== Supercomputer ====\n* [[Blue Gene/L]], dual core PowerPC 440, 700&nbsp;MHz, 2004\n* [[Blue Gene/P]], quad core PowerPC 450, 850&nbsp;MHz, 2007\n* [[Blue Gene/Q]], 18 core PowerPC A2, 1.6&nbsp;GHz, 2011\n\n=== Other ===\n* [[Exponential Technology]] [[x704]], a [[BiCMOS]] PowerPC implementation, 410 to 533&nbsp;MHz\n* [[P.A. Semi]] [[PWRficient]] PA6T-1682M, a dual-core microprocessor that runs at 2&nbsp;GHz\n\n== Embedded PowerPC ==\n\n32-bit and 64-bit PowerPC processors have been a favorite of embedded computer designers. To keep costs low on high-volume competitive products, the CPU core is usually bundled into a system-on-chip (SOC) integrated circuit. SOCs contain the processor core, cache and the processor's local data on-chip, along with clocking, timers, memory (SDRAM), peripheral (network, serial I/O), and bus (PCI, PCI-X, ROM/Flash bus, I2C) controllers. IBM also offers an open bus architecture (called [[CoreConnect]]) to facilitate connection of the processor core to memory and peripherals in a SOC design.  IBM and Motorola have competed along parallel development lines in overlapping markets. A later development was the [http://www.nxp.com/docs/en/user-guide/BOOK_EUM.pdf Book E PowerPC Specification], implemented by both IBM and Freescale Semiconductor, which defines embedded extensions to the PowerPC programming model.\n\n===AMCC===\n* [[PowerPC 400#PowerPC 440|440SP]]: 533-667&nbsp;MHz, 10/100/1G Ethernet, (2) 64bit PCI-X, 32bit PCI-X, XOR engine, 32k L1 Cache.\n* [[PowerPC 400#PowerPC 440|440SPe]]: 533-667&nbsp;MHz, 10/100/1G Ethernet, (3) 64bit PCI-Express, 64bit PCI-X, XOR engine, 32k L1 Cache.\n* [[PowerPC 400#PowerPC 440|440EPx]]: 333-667&nbsp;MHz, (2) 10/100/1G Ethernet, Hardware Security, PCI, DDR-II, FPU, USB 1.1 or USB 2.0, 32k L1 Cache.\n* [[PowerPC 400#PowerPC 440|440GR]]: 333-667&nbsp;MHz, (2) 10/100 Ethernet, (4) UART, (2) IIC, 53 GPIO, SPI, 32k L1 Cache.\n* [[PowerPC 400#PowerPC 440|440GRx]]: 333-667&nbsp;MHz, (2) 10/100/1G Ethernet, (4) UART, (2) IIC, 53 GPIO, SPI, DDR-II, Hardware Security, 32k L1 Cache.\n* PowerPC [[Titan (microprocessor)|Titan]], 32-bit, dual core, 2&nbsp;GHz. Announced, planned release in 2008\n\n===Broad Reach Engineering===\n* [[BRE440]] [[radiation hardened]] CPU based on [[PowerPC 440#PowerPC 440|PowerPC 440]] core with 256 kB L2 Cache, PCI, (2) 10/100 Ethernet, 4-CH DMA, (2) UART, extensive on chip memory control. Designed specifically for radiation environments and extreme temperature environments (such as space).\n\n===BAE Systems===\n* [[RAD750]] [[radiation hardened]] CPU based on [[PowerPC 750]] core.\n\n===Culturecom===\n* [[PowerPC 400#V-Dragon|V-Dragon]] based on [[PowerPC 400#PowerPC 405|PowerPC 405]] core.\n\n=== Cray ===\n* SeaStar, SeaStar2 and SeaStar2+, [[PowerPC 400#PowerPC 440|PowerPC 440]] based communications processors for their [[Opteron]] based [[Cray XT3|XT3]], [[Cray XT4|XT4]] and [[Cray XT5|XT5]] supercomputers.\n\n===Freescale (former Motorola)===\n* MPC8xx [[PowerQUICC#PowerQUICC I|PowerQUICC]] - networking & telecom card controllers with embedded communications module, up to 80&nbsp;MHz\n* [[MPC5xx]] - automotive & industrial controllers\n* [[PowerPC 5000#MPC51xx|MPC51xx]]/[[PowerPC 5000#MPC52xx|MPC52xx]] - [[PowerPC e300|e300]] core, automotive & industrial [[system on a chip]] (SoC) controllers, up to 466&nbsp;MHz\n* [[PowerPC 5000#MPC55xx|MPC55xx]] -  [[PowerPC e200|e200]] core, automotive & industrial controllers, up to 144&nbsp;MHz\n* [[PowerPC 5000#MPC56xx|MPC56xx]] -  [[PowerPC e200|e200]] core, automotive & industrial controllers, up to 264&nbsp;MHz\n* MPC82xx [[PowerQUICC#PowerQUICC II|PowerQUICC II]] - [[PowerPC 600#PowerPC 603|603e]] core, networking & telecom SoC controllers with high-capacity on-chip switched bus and communications module, up to 450&nbsp;MHz\n* MPC83xx [[PowerQUICC#PowerQUICC II Pro|PowerQUICC II Pro]] - [[PowerPC e300|e300]] core, networking & telecom SoC controllers with high-capacity on-chip switched bus and communications module, up to 667&nbsp;MHz\n* MPC85xx [[PowerQUICC#PowerQUICC III|PowerQUICC III]] - [[PowerPC e500|e500]] core, high end networking & telecom SoC controllers with high-capacity on-chip switched bus and communications module. D Dual core versions supporting both symmetric and asymmetric multiprocessing, up to 1.5&nbsp;GHz.\n* MPC864x - [[PowerPC e600|e600]] core, 1 MB L2 cache, improved [[AltiVec]] (out of order instructions), an embedded memory controller, Ethernet controllers, a [[RapidIO]] fabric interface, a [[PCI Express]] interface, and MPX bus. Dual core versions supporting both symmetric and asymmetric multiprocessing, up to 1.5&nbsp;GHz.\n* [[QorIQ]] Processing Platforms (evolution of the [[PowerQUICC]]). The first letter of the model indicates the series, the second and the third model number indicates the number of cores (e.g. P5040 has four cores, T4240 has 24 cores)\n** [[QorIQ#P Series|P series]]\n*** [[QorIQ#P1|P1 series]], [[PowerPC e500#e500v2|e500v2 cores]]: P1011, P1020\n*** [[QorIQ#P2|P2 series]]: [[PowerPC e500#e500v2|e500v2 core]] P2020, [[PowerPC e500#e500mc|e500mc cores]] P2040, P2041\n*** [[QorIQ#P3|P3 series]], introduced in 2010, based on [[PowerPC e500#e500mc|e500mc cores]]: P3041\n*** [[QorIQ#P4|P4 series]], introduced in 2009, based on [[PowerPC e500#e500mc|e500mc cores]]: P4080\n*** [[QorIQ#P5|P5 series]], introduced in 2012, 45&nbsp;nm process, based on [[PowerPC e5500|e5500 cores]]: P5010, P5020, P5021, P5040\n** [[QorIQ#AMP Series|T series]], introduced in 2013, all based on [[PowerPC e6500|e6500 cores]], and 28&nbsp;nm process\n*** [[QorIQ#T1|T1 series]]: T1040, T1042, T1020, T1022\n*** [[QorIQ#T2|T2 series]]: T2080, T2081\n*** [[QorIQ#T4|T4 series]]: T4240, T4160, T4080\n\n===IBM (now from AMCC)===\n* [[PowerPC 400#PowerPC 401|401]]\n* [[PowerPC 400#PowerPC 403|403]]: MMU added in most advanced version 403GCX\n* [[PowerPC 400#PowerPC 405|405]]: MMU, Ethernet, serial, PCI, SRAM, SDRAM; NPe405 adds more network devices\n* [[PowerPC 400#PowerPC 440|440]]: A range of processors based on the Book E core.\n** [[PowerPC 400#PowerPC 440|440EP]]: 333-667&nbsp;MHz, (2) 10/100 Ethernet, PCI, DDR, FPU, USB 1.1 or USB 2.0, 32k L1 Cache.\n** [[PowerPC 400#PowerPC 440|440GP]]: 400-500&nbsp;MHz, (2) 10/100 Ethernet, PCI-X, DDR, 32k L1 Cache.\n** [[PowerPC 400#PowerPC 440|440GX]]: 533-800&nbsp;MHz, (2) 10/100 Ethernet, (2) 10/100/1G Ethernet with TCP/IP hardware acceleration, PCI-X, DDR, 32k L1 Cache\n\n===Microsoft===\n*[[Xenon CPU|Xenon]] (Microsoft Xbox 360) - Three core [[Power Processing Element|PPE]]-based, 1 MB shared L2 cache, [[Altivec|VMX128]], 3.2&nbsp;GHz\n\n===Nintendo===\n*[[Gekko (microprocessor)|Gekko]] (GameCube) - 750CXe core with special enhancements, 485&nbsp;MHz\n*[[Broadway (microprocessor)|Broadway]] (Wii) - 750CL, 729&nbsp;MHz\n*[[Espresso (microprocessor)|Espresso]] (Wii U) - 3\u00d7 750 cores, 1.24&nbsp;GHz\n\n=== P.A. Semi ===\n* [[PWRficient]] PA6T-1682M: a dual core PPC running at 2&nbsp;GHz\n\n=== Rapport ===\n\n*[[Kilocore]] 1025: a CPU with a single PowerPC core and 1024 processing element (8 bit, 125&nbsp;MHz) cores (unreleased). This CPU is designed for running security and multimedia applications (with parallel processing) on portable game devices and media players.\n\n=== Xilinx ===\n* Some Virtex-II Pro and Virtex-4 [[FPGA]] have up to two embedded [[PowerPC 400#PowerPC 405|PowerPC 405]] cores,.<ref>[http://direct.xilinx.com/bvdocs/publications/ds083.pdf Virtex-II Pro datasheet] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061025211704/http://direct.xilinx.com/bvdocs/publications/ds083.pdf |date=2006-10-25 }}</ref><ref>[http://direct.xilinx.com/bvdocs/publications/ds112.pdf Virtex-4 family overview] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061015234646/http://direct.xilinx.com/bvdocs/publications/ds112.pdf |date=2006-10-15 }}</ref>\n* Virtex-5 FXT has up to two embedded PowerPC 440 cores.\n\n==Northbridge==\n[[Northbridge (computing)|Northbridge]] or host bridge for PowerPC CPU is an [[Integrated Circuit]] (IC) for interfacing PowerPC CPU with memory, and Southbridge IC. Some Northbridge also provide interface for [[Accelerated Graphics Port]]s (AGP) bus, [[Peripheral Component Interconnect]] (PCI), PCI-X, PCI Express, or [[Hypertransport]] bus. Specific Northbridge IC must be used for PowerPC CPU. It is impossible to use Northbridge for Intel or AMD x86 CPU with PowerPC CPU. However it is possible to use certain types of x86 [[Southbridge (computing)|Southbridge]] in PowerPC based motherboards. Example: [[VIA Technologies|VIA]] 686B and [[AMD]] Geode CS5536.\n\nList of Northbridge for PowerPC:\n*IBM:\n**CPC 700 and CPC 710 for IBM PowerPC 750 series.\n**CPC 925 and CPC 945 for IBM PowerPC 970 series.\n*Motorola (now available from Tundra):\n**MPC-105\n**MPC-106\n**MPC-107\n*Mentor Arc Inc. (MAI).\n**Articia S.\n*[[Marvell Technology Group|Marvell]] Discovery series for Motorola MPC74xx and MPC75x and IBM 750 series CPU.\n**Discovery ( GT-64260A, GT-64261A and GT-64262A).\n**Discovery LT (MV64420 and MV64430).\n**Discovery II (MV64360, MV6361 and MV6362).\n**Discovery III (MV64460, MV6461 and MV6462).\n**Discovery V (MV 64560).\n**Discovery VI(MV 64660).\n*Philips Semiconductor\n**VAS96011 and VAS96012: Two IC northbridge for PowerPC 603 and PowerPC 604.\n*Tundra (Canada)\n**TSI-106 (formerly Motorola MPC-106).\n**TSI-107 (formerly Motorola MPC-107) / XPC107APX series.\n**TSI-108\n**TSI-109\n**TSI-110\n**Qspan II - PCI bus interface for PowerPC CPU.\n**PowerPro (CA91L750) - Memory controller for PowerPC CPU.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Lists of microprocessors|PowerPC processors]]\n[[Category:PowerPC microprocessors|*]]\n", "name_user": "Bumm13", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eMicrosoft:changed \"Xenon CPU\" (Xenon) wikilink to \"Xenon (processor)\"", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_PowerPC_processors"}
{"title_page": "Jim J. Bullock", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n|name= Jim J. Bullock\n|image=\n|image_size=\n|caption=\n|birth_name= James Jackson Bullock\n|birth_date= {{Birth date and age|1955|02|9}}<ref name=desert_sun_20110123>{{cite news |url=http://www.mydesert.com/article/20110123/LIFESTYLES01/101220352/Jim-J-Bullock-plays-dual-role-Clown-HIV-survivor |newspaper=[[The Desert Sun]] |location=Palm Springs |first=Judith |last=Salkin |title=Jim J. Bullock plays dual role: Clown, HIV survivor |date=January 23, 2011 |accessdate=June 7, 2016 |url-status=unfit |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110128072802/http://www.mydesert.com/article/20110123/LIFESTYLES01/101220352/Jim-J-Bullock-plays-dual-role-Clown-HIV-survivor |archivedate=January 28, 2011 }}</ref>\n|birth_place= [[Casper, Wyoming]], U.S.\n|other_names= Jm J. Bullock\n|occupation= Actor, comedian\n|years_active= 1980\u2013present\n|spouse=\n|website=\n}}\n'''James Jackson Bullock''' (born February 9, 1955), sometimes credited as '''Jim J. Bullock''' or '''Jm J. Bullock''', is an American [[actor]] and [[comedian]] of [[theatre|stage]], [[television program|television]] and [[film|motion pictures]].\n\n==Early life==\nBullock was born in [[Casper, Wyoming]], and raised in [[Odessa, Texas]] (although  he is listed as an alumnus of [[Natrona County High School]] ([[Casper, Wyoming]])), and was raised in a [[Southern Baptist Convention|Southern Baptist]] home and as a youth, planned to become an evangelical Christian minister.<ref name=desert_sun_20110123/> He received a music scholarship to attend [[Oklahoma Baptist University]] in [[Shawnee, Oklahoma]], but left school without graduating.<ref name=advocate_19990720>{{cite magazine| url=https://www.questia.com/magazine/1G1-55183037/the-comeback-kidder| magazine=[[The Advocate (LGBT magazine)|The Advocate]]| first=Bohdan| last=Zachary| title=The Comeback Kidder| date=July 20, 1999| accessdate=14 September 2018| via=[[Questia Online Library]]}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nBullock became a notable entertainment figure in the 1980s when he co-starred on the [[Situation comedy|sitcom]] ''[[Too Close for Comfort]]'' as Monroe Ficus (credited as \"Jm J. Bullock\") and was a regular guest on [[John Davidson (entertainer)|John Davidson]]'s updated version of ''[[Hollywood Squares]]''; Bullock occasionally substituted for Davidson as host.<ref name=\"av140615\">{{cite news |first1=Marah |last1=Eakin |first2=John |last2=Teti |first3=Erik |last3=Adams |newspaper=[[The A.V. Club]] |title=Bonus round stars: 9 celebrities who found their greatest fame on game shows |url=http://www.avclub.com/article/bonus-round-stars-9-celebrities-who-found-their-gr-205592 |date=June 16, 2014 |accessdate=June 20, 2014}}</ref> He also appeared as a semi-regular on ''[[Battlestars (game show)|Battlestars]]''. He later became a semi-regular on ''[[ALF (TV series)|ALF]]'' (from 1989 to 1990) as Neal Tanner. He guest-hosted a special episode of ''[[Double Dare (Nickelodeon game show)|Super Sloppy Double Dare]]'' in 1989 where host [[Marc Summers]] and announcer [[Harvey (announcer)|Harvey]] played against each other. The game ended with both Summers and Harvey playing the Obstacle Course and winning all eight prizes for their respective civilian teammates. Stage assistants Robin Marrella and Dave Shikiar guest-announced that episode.\n\nAfter ''ALF'' went off the air in 1990, Bullock remained active with [[theatre]], [[television]], and [[film]] work. He briefly hosted a syndicated [[talk show]] with ex-[[televangelist]] [[Tammy Faye Messner]]. The ''Jim J. and Tammy Faye Show'' debuted in 1996, but Messner exited the program a few months later following a cancer diagnosis. Bullock continued with new co-host, Ann Abernathy, and the show became ''The Jim J. and Ann Show'' until it was canceled.\n\nBullock was the voice of ''[[Queer Duck]]'' in the animated series of cartoons of the same name which have appeared on both the [[internet]] and the cable TV network [[Showtime (TV network)|Showtime]]. In 2000, Bullock was a regular panelist on the revival of ''[[I've Got a Secret]]''. He also performed on the national tour of the [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] production ''[[Hairspray (musical)|Hairspray]]'' as Wilbur Turnblad, a role he took to the Broadway stage starting September 18, 2007. Some of his other noteworthy roles include the pilled-up narcoleptic Prince [[Valium]] in the 1987 [[Mel Brooks]] movie ''[[Spaceballs]]'', and the \"Not-Quite-Out-of-the-Closet\" character in the date montage at the beginning of 2001's ''[[Kissing Jessica Stein]]''. From 2004 to 2007, he had a recurring role as Mr. Monroe, a teacher at the fictional James K. Polk Middle School on the [[Nickelodeon]] live action sitcom ''[[Ned's Declassified School Survival Guide]]''.\n\n==Personal life==\nIn 1985, while ''Too Close For Comfort'' was being retooled as ''The Ted Knight Show'', Bullock learned that he was [[HIV]] positive. He made his diagnosis public 11 years later.<ref name=\"nydn\">{{cite news |last1=Sacks |first1=Ethan |title=Before Charlie Sheen, here are other celebrities whose HIV-positive diagnoses or contracting of AIDS shocked fans |url=https://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/gossip/celebrities-hiv-positive-aids-article-1.2436964 |accessdate=20 June 2019 |work=New York Daily News |date=23 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 1996, Bullock's partner of six years, John Casey, died from [[AIDS]]-related complications.<ref name=desert_sun_20110123/><ref name=advocate_19990720/>  Bullock is a longtime survivor of the virus and, as of 2018, was still healthy due in part to [[antiretroviral drug]]s.<ref name=desert_sun_20110123/><ref name=usatoday_20010606>{{cite news| url=https://www.usatoday.com/news/health/spotlight/2001-06-06-bullock-aids.htm| newspaper=[[USA Today]]| first=Mike| last=Falcon| title=Jim J. Bullock reflects on AIDS anniversary| date=June 6, 2001| accessdate=January 23, 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn February 17, 1999, Bullock was arrested outside a bar in [[West Hollywood, California]], for possession of [[crystal meth]], and was sentenced to probation.<ref name=advocate_19990720/><ref>{{cite magazine| url=http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20131630,00.html| title=Too Close for Comfort: 1980-1985| magazine=[[People (magazine)|People]]| date=26 June 2000| accessdate=18 December 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Genre !! width=\"60\" | Year !! Title !! Role !! Episodes !! Notes\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| TV series || align=\"center\" |1980\u20131987 || ''[[Too Close for Comfort]]'' || Monroe Ficus ||  || 118 episodes\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| Film || align=\"center\" |1981 || ''[[Full Moon High]]'' || Eddie ||  || credited as Jm. Bullock<br>Alternative title: ''Moon High''\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| Film || align=\"center\" |1987 || ''[[Spaceballs]]'' || Prince Valium ||  || credited as JM J. Bullock\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| Film || align=\"center\" |1988 || ''[[DeGarmo and Key|DeGarmo & Key]]: Rock Solid...The Rock-u-mentary!'' || News Reporter ||  || \n|-valign=\"top\"\n| TV series || align=\"center\" |1989 || ''[[Double Dare (franchise)|Super Sloppy Double Dare]]'' || Himself/Guest Host ||  || \n|-valign=\"top\"\n| TV series || align=\"center\" |1989\u20131990 || ''[[ALF (TV series)|ALF]]'' || Neal Tanner || \"He Ain't Heavy, He's Willie's Brother\" <br/> \"The First Time Ever I Saw Your Face\" <br/> \"Break Up to Make Up\" <br/> \"Happy Together\"<br/> \"Love on the Rocks\" || {{hs|00}}5 episodes\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| Film || align=\"center\" |1991 || ''[[Switch (1991 film)|Switch]]'' || {{hs|Psychic}}The Psychic ||  || \n|-valign=\"top\"\n| TV series || align=\"center\" |1992 || ''[[Seinfeld]]'' || Flight Attendant #1 || \"{{sortname|The|Airport}}\" || \n|-valign=\"top\"\n|Music Video|| align=\"center\" |1994|| ''[[Bubba Hyde]]'' || Bubba Hyde || \"[[Diamond Rio]] song\" ||\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| TV series || align=\"center\" |1994\u20131995 || ''[[Boogies Diner]]'' || Gerald ||  || unknown episodes\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| Animated TV series || align=\"center\" |1994 || ''[[Duckman|Duckman: Private Dick/Family Man]]'' ||  || \"Cellar Beware\" || [[Voice acting|voice actor]]\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| TV series || align=\"center\" |1996 || ''[[Roseanne]]'' || Al || \"Satan, Darling\" || \n|-valign=\"top\"\n| Animated TV series || align=\"center\" |1999 || ''[[Queer Duck]]'' || Adam Seymour \"Queer Duck\" Duckstein ||  || [[Voice acting|voice actor]]; 20 episodes\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| TV series || align=\"center\" |2000 || ''[[E! True Hollywood Story]]'' || Himself || \"Jim J. Bullock\" || documentary\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| Documentary || align=\"center\" |2000 || ''{{sortname|The|Eyes of Tammy Faye}}'' || Himself ||  || \n|-valign=\"top\"\n| Film || align=\"center\" |2000 || ''[[Get Your Stuff]]'' || Tom ||  || \n|-valign=\"top\"\n| Film || align=\"center\" |2001 || ''[[10 Attitudes]]'' || Tex ||  || \n|-valign=\"top\"\n| Film || align=\"center\" |2001 || ''[[Kissing Jessica Stein]]'' || Not-Yet-Out Gay Guy (Craig) ||  || \n|-valign=\"top\"\n| Film || align=\"center\" |2001 || ''[[Circuit (film)|Circuit]]'' || Mark ||  || \n|-valign=\"top\"\n| TV series || align=\"center\" |2001 || ''[[Intimate Portrait]]'' || Himself || \"Tammy Faye\" || documentary\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| TV series || align=\"center\" |2001 || ''[[Popular (TV series)|Popular]]'' || Judge || \"{{hs|Brain Game}}The Brain Game\" || \n|-valign=\"top\"\n| Short film || align=\"center\" |2002 || ''[[Gaydar (film)|Gaydar]]'' || Maurice's Ex ||  || 20 minutes <br/> included in the [[Direct-to-video]] compilation film ''Men's Mix 1: Gay Shorts Collection''\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| TV series || align=\"center\" |2004\u20132007 || ''[[Ned's Declassified School Survival Guide]]'' || Mr. Monroe || || {{hs|0}}18 episodes total\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| TV series || align=\"center\" |2005 || ''{{sortname|The|Bold and the Beautiful}}'' || Serge, Wedding Planner ||  || {{hs|00}}2 episodes; 12 episodes tota